                            CDC Executive Gray, Police Scuffle Over PartyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Emblem on Car.
see stroy

 Allegations of elections day campaigning dampened voting at the Capital Bye Pass precinct in Central Monrovia Tuesday later resulting into a sea of confusion and argument between the Liberia National Police and Acarous Gray, Secretary General of the Congress for Democratic Change.

At issue were concerns by LNP officers that Gray should not have taken a party vehicle with the partyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s emblem at the center where he went to cast his ballot.

Gray told reporters present during his scuffle with the LNP that the confusion started after he was ordered by LNP officer Darlington George to remove his partyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s initial from his vehicle which he refused to do.

Gray further explained that the vehicle was parked in front of his house and that he was not carrying any campaign material. Gray said to his surprise, the next thing he saw was a Police car which came close to hitting his vehicle. Gray further explained that the next thing he noticed was Officer George getting down from his vehicle and ordering him not to use the vehicle any more.

Ã¢â‚¬Å“You know it is unfortunate that a guy like that lacks moral credentials because if you go all around you will see Ellen Johnson Sirleaf posters, in front of her house, at the Antoinette Tubman Stadium (ATS), go all over the City of Monrovia, you will see her photos, campaign materials all over which officer George did not consider a violation. So why am I in violation,Ã¢â‚¬Â Gray said.

The CDC Secretary General narrated that he was approached in a very rude and unorganized manner which he says was a violation of his human rights.

report: This so sad for us as Liberia. For starters, it's a bad image to portray to an international community we are trying to attract for further developmental progress in our country. Most importantly, it's scary for us as Liberia and disappointing  that we have to constantly be presented  with these kinds of uprisings that makes us question if we will ever be able to abandon some of the vigilante attributes acquired during our war in an effort to move forward. Barkue, thanks for reporting what you are witnessing as you have that right that some of us understand and appreciate. From my understanding you spoke to a situation unfolding in the country from your viewpoint. I don't recall you accusing any one group of people as being the culprits. You only mentioned CDC in reference to their headquarters being an area marker for the conflict YOU are witnessing. We need to respect each other and realize that Liberia, our future, is much bigger than party preferences!

report: Thank you for your independent observation Desmond Diggs. It makes no sense for people who have been peaceful all of this time, to start to cause unnecessary problems now. I think that we need to pay very close attention to whats going on, AS Liberia. First, there is a media campaign against CDC, framing them as people who want to bring war, break the law, and get into power by all means. THIS IS UNTRUE, if you have followed the elections without being aligned with any party. Even during their campaign during the 1st round elections, their rally was guarded and blocked by UNMIL and LNP. The people did not allow this to push them, they went on peacefully as the vowed to. Honestly, in regards to the LNP and UNMIL, I am not at all surprised. POWER BY ALL MEANS. Ellen is a war criminal, there is no way she would allow people to demonstrate against her insistence to rule this nation. Violence against peaceful protesters is a very deep problem, which if not resolved, could spark up tension in Liberia.
author: Laura Wilson

report:
We are all Liberia! Violence affects us all. Peace helps us all! Please, I beg you all think before you write.  Know when you write that your words have the power to heal and to hurt.  We all have different ideas of how our government should function and how our country should be governed and that makes us Liberia.  We always have an opinion. Now is the time to recognize that that alone makes us all teammates.  We are all on the Liberia team.  

With our power, speak peace to each other.  We differ but we are not different! Elections are hard especially when your candidate does not win and thank God there are numerous chances every six years to give your candidate another chance to campaign and run to hold the highest office in the land. Be for your candidate without being against your fellow Liberia.

16 years we gave War a chance and it destroyed us all.  Give Peace a chance..it will continue to build us up. The children are counting on us!

God first, Liberia prominent!

STATE OF SIEGE - a declaration that may suspend some normal functions of the executive, legislative and judicial powers, alert citizens to change their normal behaviours, or order government agencies to implement emergency preparedness plans. report:
Retyped from the Heritage Vol. 17 No. 9 November 7, 2011

Republic of Liberia
National Elections Commission
Press Release

The National Elections Commission (NEC) wishes to categorically state that there is no constitutional or statuatory provision under Liberia Laws that allows withdraws of a candidate or party at this stage of the electoral process.

There is a specified procedure for withdrawal of a candidate, political party, coalition, or alliance as provided for in the candidate nomination procedure for the 2011 elections.

The procedure states that "where the Commission has approved the candidature of an independent candidate, political party, coalition, alliance, or candidate of such parties.

Such candidate may be withdrawn by submitting a Declaration of Withdrawal Form (CN-11) to the Commission, only under the signatures of the head of party, coalition, or alliance and the candidate.

Candidates must submit the forms no later than forty-eight hours before the publication of the Final List of Candidates.  In the case of an independent candidate, his/her signature shall be sufficient notice of such withdrawal.  No independent candidate, political party, coalition, alliance or candidate of such parties may withdraw an approved candidature after the final list of candidates has been published.

Consistent with Article 83(b) of the 1986 Constitution of the Republic of Liberia, the NEC wishes to assure the people of Liberia that the November 8 Presidential Run-off election will be held as scheduled.  Contrary to the Congress for Democratic Change allegation that its grievances were not addressed, the NEC states that all complaints from the CDC are been given due process.

An official invitation was extended to the CDC for a meeting with the NEC on November, 2011 to discuss issues raised to its letter to the NEC on November 1, 2011 but the meeting was not honored by the CDC.

It should be recalled that on five different occasions, the CDC requested postponement of its own case for various reasons, including gathering and preparation of witnesses.  To date, the CDC has not completed that process; as a result, the case is still pending.

Meanwhile, all activities befitting the Presidential Run-off election, including the training of poll staff, packaging and deployment of electoral materials across the country, as well as security protection for the entire process are progressing as planned.  The NEC is therefore calling on all registered voters to turnout en mass on November 8, 2011 to exercise their Constitutional franchise by peacefully voting for the leaders of their choice.

UP voters will also be reluctant to turn out because they'll feel their party has already won (why get that ugly ink on your finger if your party will win). In addition, the leadership saves face from a massive defeat (esp.  with both Prince Johnson and Charles Brumskine supporting UP)...they can always argue: hey, we really did not lose...we were not in the elections anyway. report: Update On CDC Clash: Was out and about a short while to get first hand details on CDC demo this afternoon. Happened that CDC supporters left their compound and moved on to the street in the vicinity of Old Road Injunction. Were stopped by police officers on orders not to allow the march to go, as they never had permit to carry on. As the crowd was very huge, the force was gradually breaking the police defence line and pockets of rampaging rioters found alternative routes on the road heading to Kailondo and from there began surging in the direction of the old road junction. At this point, the Police fired tear gas to disperse the rushing crowd. Moments later, gunfire was heard ringing over Congo town. Spoke to one police officer and he said the gunfire came from the direction of CDC headquarters. Spoke to some CDC supporters and they claimed the shooting was directed in the crowd. Things are still sketchy but various reports are citing at least one dead, though CDC supporters claim three persons were killed.  We are following the developments......

report: i'm really saddened by the ongoing violence in Liberia.  Regardless of the differences, the leadership of all sides concerned should see reason to appeal to partisans to leave the streets.   This is not something that should be done hours from now.  The situation has deteriorated enough and should be done now.    The government should also take every step to use non-lethal force.  Let leaders rise above differences and seek first the long term interests of the nation.      We must also condemn with a strong voice, any side that attempts to disrupt voting tomorrow or threaten voters who do choose to go to the polls.

report:
When my brother W. Gyude Moore, first added me to this forum I thought it an exciting chance to engage in constructive debate on the central issues confronting Liberia (and we all love politics). However, I quickly realised that the group had degenerated into a forum for "partisan rum shop arguments" and so I refrained from commentary. At times I even chastised my brother for the tone of his contributions. 

The tone in  this group is reflected on the streets of Monrovia today. It saddens me to see that even as the events of today unfold the harsh and non-constructive tone and divisive language of some of Liberia's most gifted and fortuitous children continues. Most of the Participants of this group represent many of Liberia's most talented and privileged the onus is on all of us to exercise greater responsibility. 

I encourage you guys to try to engage in more constructive debates tone the rhetoric down and lets just hope and hope that this thing has a positive resolution. Many of you have not much to loose living abroad but there are REAL  people with lives at stake here!!

report: Liberia National Police, like many other aspects of our country's path to recovery is flawed. Police show of force today using lethal weapons was WRONG in all shapes and form; CDC protest escalation into rioting was UNLawful...Keep in mind, a strong and stable Liberia will require law enforcement that is trained on all aspects...simply vilifying the LNP, CDCians and rest of the gov't is not gonna help anyone...Let's seek justice but let's seek how and what can be done to push Liberia forward. Don't stall with too much focus on what's wrong, let's focus on how we can fix it. It's sad that the very power to fix it - VOTES will not be utilized (CDC's boycott). Nonetheless, Liberia is on a path to recovery and it's up to us to decide if we want to spend the next couple of days/weeks/months/yrs down in the trenches, fighting among ourselves on who's better and who's more evil, stalling our progress while the rest of the world goes on...OR find ways that WE can move forward. Power to make the right changes is not inherently tied to "elections" or having the "seat of authority". Leadership comes in all forms and leadership that will help Liberia is one that will unite us ALL and bring True peace and reconciliation. Now THIS is on us ALL! We lost lives today, let us not lose our Country! #Pray4Peace #RIP

report: Courtesy of WIKI-OUT LIBERIA INVESTIGATORS:Fellow contributors, as u all may know, i informed you all about a very sensitive information THAT I GOT YESTERDAY FROM THE CONGRESS FOR DEMOCRATIC CHANGE (CDC)  revealing  how the CDC had  planned to  protest in mornovia so as to  disrupt the electoral process in the name of a peace macrh. In that post, i hinted that there were planns by the CDC to besiege the city and its envrions, but some colleagues chose to debunk me on the issue. Moses Brown of the Women Democracy radio even went as far as lavishing insults at me. But as i always indicated that i will never post lie on this page, the CDC definately proved me right today. Their "civil or peaceful protest"  placed the entire city under hostage today. Shops and marketeers were force to  close down before their normal closing hours. Now, as i post this piece, the CDC zealots are still regrouping themselves at their congo town headquarters to continue their  mayhem which left the newly built and higly praised gas station of george kailondo completely vandalized today to other areas mainly new kru town, vai town, clara town, red-light, duala and central monrovia. the aim of these planned act is to instill fear into the minds of voters so that they can be prevented form casting their votes in the impending run-off polls, according to what i am gathering from a secret CDC meeting which is ongoing now at the last floor of their congo town headquarters. According to waht i have also gathered, they will also be parrading with the caskets of those who were allegedly killed today in the streets during this protest. they will latter take the corpses to the US embassy, ECOWA, CHINESE EMBASSY, AND THE OFFFICES OF THE AU.AFTER WHICH, THE WILL NOW PROCEED TO A LOCAL FUNERAL HOME where the  BODIES would be kept for FOR BURIAL.

report:
It is sadden that we are engaging in activities that have the potential to undermine the fragile peace we currently enjoy without reflecting our most recent past. The gathering should have been peaceful as claimed by CDC but it turned violent when stones were threw from the crowd, shortly followed by the PoliceÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s reaction. So so sadden having viewed the pictures on the internet. Therefore, I would like to use this medium to appeal to the consciousness of all Liberia to refrain from all acts of violence and engage in constructive dialogue to mend our differences. There are always better alternatives, violence cannot resolve any problem, rather deepen the wounds, breed hatred and to a greater extend make us insensitive to the general well-being of society.
Chapter 1 Article 1 of the constitution reads: "All power is inherent in the people. All free governments are instituted by their authority and for their benefit and they have the right to alter and reform the same when their safety and happiness so require. In order to ensure democratic government which responds to the wishes of the governed, the people shall have the right at such period, and in such manner as provided for under this constitution to cause their public servants to leave office and to fill vacancies by elections and appointments". In my opinion, as provided for under the constitution, it is the right of all Liberia (18 + and properly registered electorate) to exercise their franchise in the electoral process. As such, under on condition should this right be denied or people be coaxed from exercising it. If for whatsoever reasons people are happy/unhappy with the current regime, simply vote ELLEN orWinstonTubman but remember to have Liberia at heart in making that decision, in terms of, who can transform the country, reconcile the people and make the country a better place for our children children... Finally, my sympathy to those who sustain loss and God Bless Liberia and steer her through this storm.Amen

report: Liberia National Police has begun shutting down radio and TV stations presumed loyal to opposition party Congress for Democratic Change.  Police Director Marc Amblard confirmed the move late Monday night, on the eve of the November 8 presidential run-off, following the riot at the CDC headquarters in which there was at least one casualty and several wounded.  Since the riot, CDC Secretary General Acarous Gray has been on air making statements the Justice Ministry describes as "inflammatory and unnecessary".  Mr. Amblard says "a writ from the court" orders the police to remove from the airwaves the following stations: Benoni Urey's Love FM and TV; George Weah's King's FM; and Aaron Kollie's Power FM and TV.

report: Still amazing to me what happened today. Thinking about it seriously for hours now and have really not come to a logical conclusion on what the security officers meant by their indiscriminate shooting actions today. Granted the proposed rally or march was ill-legal and also that the Cdcians became violent to an extent, did it warrant shooting to hurt and kill in this manner? The government claimed there was exchange of gun fire between both parties, CDC and the security officers, but up to the time of the press conference, there was absolutely no information regarding injury to the security officers as a result of shooting from CDC's  end. Heard from the Justice Minister that a stone thrown at one of the Nigerian officer led him to fire live bullet which resulted to a death, could tear gas not have been the appropriate countering option in that situation?

report: The reason why I'm calling u you out on this is because since the incidence this morning, all you've done is play the victim role here...and continue to push the US vs. Them. Yes, CDCians lost their lives today but we consider them as Liberia!! and it did not have to come to this. Since this morning, I have yet to hear you or the CDC leaders come out and denounce the violence and call for restraint. All I've seen here are calls for retribution and demands for justice or "struggle continue". Where's the responsibility on the part of the leadership on the destruction of property, businesses,  lawlessness exhibited today. I have always been one of those that have cautioned against people calling CDCians thugs and applying the violence tag to them, but where's the call for calm, reasoning and tolerance? Should ur leaders be making statements about "even if I'd have to die"...is this a time for martyrdom??? The tone on both ends are wrong, the protests/riots were wrong! Police brutality was wrong! We need both sides to take responsibility.

report: Fellow Liberia. Today's event at the CDC headquarter marks a sad event in our post war history as several young fellow Liberia woke up this morning, left their families, to participate in what was to be a peaceful rally. I lived near there, and saw the crowd gathering and parading in the front of my home chanting their various slogans in re not voting tomorrow. It is tragic for unarmed Liberia no matter the provocation, to loose their lives. I am sure the matter will be investigated and the facts should come eventually. However, this incidence is evident of a fragile peace we enjoy in Liberia, and our struggle to navigate the complexities of "democracy." I pray that our leaders, will step back take a deep look into themselves, and accept that we are all connected, one small family, only a few cousins removed, and that when the dust settle, we all still have to live in this our Liberia. The foundation of democracy is the element of compromise - winner does not always have to take all. It is the great compromises that strengthens the foundation of democracy. At the end of the day we all win when our leaders see it befitting to come to the table to sort things out peacefully in the interest of national unity and growth. Liberia has come along way in such a short time, but we have a long way to go. We can only get there through unity, peace and mutual respect for our diversity and differences. Whenever a young life is lost, a part of our future is lost. Whenever an elder is lost, a part of our history is lost. We must do more to care for those most vulnerable and show greater compassion for one another. The level of disrespect shown to one another in these times are not healthy for such a fragile democracy that has so much to loose. I hope the government will investigate this matter to ensure it does not happen again. We have a disenfranchised youth population - we know this is the region's problem. As we have seen with the Arab Spring, when you have too many young people who feel that our leaders government and non-government, are not working in their interest although they represent the majority, we have a problem. I often say to Liberia abroad - find the opportunity to pay someone tuition in Liberia. Help a young person. So many friends in Liberia are supporting the youth, employing them, paying their tuition, helping them - these folks are our unsung heroes. We all have to chip in and find a way to address this problem. At the end of the day, we are all a few cousins removed. I am proud to be a Liberia, but am sad that today saw the lost of the lives of young Liberia. In peace.

report:
It is sadden that we are engaging in activities that have the potential to undermine the fragile peace we currently enjoy without reflecting our most recent past. The gathering should have been peaceful as claimed by CDC but it turned violent when stones were threw from the crowd, shortly followed by the PoliceÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s reaction. So so sadden having viewed the pictures on the internet. Therefore, I would like to use this medium to appeal to the consciousness of all Liberia to refrain from all acts of violence and engage in constructive dialogue to mend our differences. There are always better alternatives, violence cannot resolve any problem, rather deepen the wounds, breed hatred and to a greater extend make us insensitive to the general well-being of society.
Chapter 1 Article 1 of the constitution reads: "All power is inherent in the people. All free governments are instituted by their authority and for their benefit and they have the right to alter and reform the same when their safety and happiness so require. In order to ensure democratic government which responds to the wishes of the governed, the people shall have the right at such period, and in such manner as provided for under this constitution to cause their public servants to leave office and to fill vacancies by elections and appointments". In my opinion, as provided for under the constitution, it is the right of all Liberia (18 + and properly registered electorate) to exercise their franchise in the electoral process. As such, under on condition should this right be denied or people be coaxed from exercising it. If for whatsoever reasons people are happy/unhappy with the current regime, simply vote ELLEN orWinstonTubman but remember to have Liberia at heart in making that decision, in terms of, who can transform the country, reconcile the people and make the country a better place for our children children... Finally, my sympathy to those who sustain loss and God Bless Liberia and steer her through this storm.Amen

report: Still amazing to me what happened today. Thinking about it seriously for hours now and have really not come to a logical conclusion on what the security officers meant by their indiscriminate shooting actions today. Granted the proposed rally or march was ill-legal and also that the Cdcians became violent to an extent, did it warrant shooting to hurt and kill in this manner? The government claimed there was exchange of gun fire between both parties, CDC and the security officers, but up to the time of the press conference, there was absolutely no information regarding injury to the security officers as a result of shooting from CDC's end. Heard from the Justice Minister that a stone thrown at one of the Nigerian officers led him to fire live bullet which from my judgement may have resulted to the death in question so far, could tear gas not have been the appropriate countering option in that situation?

report: It's been quite a sad day in Liberia and it takes us all down memory lane. What actually surprises me about these riots are the fact the WinstonTubman is quoted as threatening to create a situation of condition of war if the run-off was not delay for a month. Day after that threat a supposed-to-be peace party rally ended up as a running battle with police and peacekeepers. I strongly feel Amb.WinstonTubman needs to be held responsible for Monday's riot and all the chaos that ensued. Incitement that leads to or engenders violence is a punishable crime. In 2005, when the CDC looked the leading political party and campaigned on indigenous lines,WinstonTubman threatened at a forum by the National Mandingo Caucus that any attempt to exclude his 'Congo' people would mean war. Amb.WinstonTubman unsuccessfully tried to denied the report, claiming he was not a man of violence. People change with times, and maybeWinstonTubman has changed for the worst. Can he answer to how and why the property of Kailondo was vandalized? What has the private citizens got to do with the electoral protest. I thinkWinstonTubman needs to be charged, tried and if guilty jailed at the Post Stockade, one of the relics left by his tyrannical uncle.

report: During the Liberia civil war, one of the many peace talks was arranged in Burkina Faso. Fearing deep acrimony and possible violence, the Burkinabe hosts separated the Liberia by factions and posted guards to keep them from each other. On the morning of the first day people recognized old friends they hadn't seen in years. Some of the had been classmates, school mates and in-laws. They were soon laughing, patting each other on the back and catching up as if they did not represent warring factions.  The guards proved superfluous - unnecessary. Here we are again. Regardless of our passion and politics, we share this bond. Some young Liberia(s) left home this morning to participate in a form of political expression. There is a Liberia mother (or mothers) second guessing her choices tonight and grieving over a child whose laughter she will never hear again. As a people we have paid such a steep price for the peace we have - today we overcharged ourselves. We were ripped off. Enough blood has been shed. While some may be more responsible than others - as Liberia we share a collective responsibility for the state of our body politic. It ought not to be like this. It really needn't be.

report: FOOLISHNESS! That's not Ellen's method of operation Rob and you know this quite well... Stop trying to misappropriate the actions of a few trigger happy Liberia Police officers as orders from the Commander in Chief. This exact behavior was sparked between the supporters of the opposition and ECOMOG six years ago when Ellen won that race against Weah, and today we witnessed it again. How about theWinstonTubman and Weah camp adhering to the countless warnings to refrain from inciting violence in their supporters or making erroneous statements about 'who will pay or what act of violence you or whoever intent to inflict on our president? report:
Statement by President Obama on the Presidential Elections in Liberia
 
The Liberia people will go to the polls tomorrow to elect the next President of Liberia.  This historic vote is an opportunity for Liberia to strengthen the countryÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s democracy, and to deepen its peace, prosperity and national unity.  We encourage all voters of all political preferences to exercise their universal right to participate in the democratic process Ã¢â‚¬â€œ all Liberia should have the ability to exercise this right without fear of violence or intimidation. 
 
Liberia has taken important steps to consolidate its democracy since the end of its civil war.  Those gains must not be setback by individuals who seek to disrupt the political process.  The international community will hold accountable those who choose to obstruct the democratic process.  We encourage all security forces in Liberia to exercise maximum restraint and to allow peaceful protest.  And we commend all that international election observers, the United Nations Mission in Liberia (UNMIL), the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), and the Liberia people are doing to ensure a free, fair, and peaceful run-off election.
 
The United States is deeply committed to its historic relationship with Liberia and its people.  We are also deeply committed to the strength of democracy on the African continent.  In that spirit, we will continue to strongly support the success of a peaceful democratic process for the Liberia people, and the peace and prosperity of Liberia.

report:
When the reason for which people aspire to plunge into leadership isn't to be servants of the people for whom they are or will be sworn into office...when their concept of leadership is in utter disparity with their professed ideologies...the ramification of their impoverished motives becomes virtually predictable. Our Liberia story is weird and deep...it is a story within a story...it is a story wrapped in greed, misconception, division...it is a story such that if demystified in ways that the ordinary Liberia can digest and apply meaning to...if it is crystallised in a manner that people, upon surgically analysing and applying common sense/logic to (thereby inadvertently emancipating themselves from the claws of illusion and hypnosis) can be better suited to make the best of decisions...decisions that affect them directly or indirectly. 

An ill-informed society is sick; it is a society that is characteristically stranded between delusion and hopelessness. The result of an ill-informed and underserved society that is on the verge of crumbling under the whims of mission-driven ideologues was, again, witnessed today. A day of gloom and profound sense of apprehension best describes the unfoldings in the only place we've come to know as our home. Disturbing/graphic photos of Liberia drowned in their own blood have jammed my iPhone...not to mention those, for no justifiable reasons of their making, that lost their lives. Yet, there are those who have opted to make light of the situation. Thinkering around the edges of reality isn't the way forward.
author: Varney Clarke

report:
Democracy does not have to be so sad
Joseph Saah Fallah

I am saddened by the news of the death of an ordinary Liberia citizen today. No matter our political persuasions, no Liberia citizen deserves to die under such circumstances -- it did not have to happen! 

While this is clearly not the time to play partisan politics, the awful incident of today should be a reminder to all Liberia that, although we have come a long way, after 14 dreadful years of senseless wars, we still have a far way to go in reconciling our differences, promoting peace, and abiding by the Laws of the Country.

 It is a complete paradox that, in the name of democracy, we are willing to invite anarchy -- in the name of democracy, we are willing to create enemies -- and in the name of democracy, we are willing to take our beloved Liberia 50 more years backwards -- as if more than 14 years of senseless fighting had not done enough damage. 

My brother and sisters, today is not a day for partisan politics -- it is one for personal reflection and introspection. Each Liberia must ask: what have I done or what am I doing to promote or perpetuate the lingering hatred -- the lingering division amongst our people? Oh, yes, we must ask ourselves and search deeply inward and find the answers -- and not only find the answers -- but we must commit ourselves to positive change! 

IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m reminded about a very unfortunate incident in the State of Arizona, about a year ago -- the incident in which U.S. Representative Giffords was shot and seriously injured and many of her staffs and ordinary citizens were fatally shot. I also remember that this incident occurred during a time of intense political bickering between Democrats and Republicans in Washington D.C. 

I can also remember that many Americans squarely placed the blame of the Arizona tragedy on the charged political atmosphere that existed in Washington D.C. during that time -- Congress vs. the White House -- Democrats vs. Republicans. And oh, many members of Congress also quickly recognized that the level of political bickering had reached all time high and needed to be tuned down -- unfortunately, it had to take the Arizona tragedy to pull the plug -- and maybe because the tragedy was too close to home! 

It is fair now to say that the political bickering in Washington D.C. that preceded the Arizona tragedy has been immensely reduced, although differences amongst politicians remained perfectly intact. I have particularly recognized that Sarah Palin, one of the politicians blamed for promoting the charged political environment that may have contributed to the Arizona tragedy, primarily for her fiery political rhetoric, has been conspicuously absent from the political scene since then. Many pundits have speculated that Sarah PalinÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s political career has been greatly harmed by the Arizona tragedy  

In my opinion, these politicians have done the right thing -- tuning down the rhetoric -- not because they are weak -- but because they are strong. They have come to the recognition that intense political bickering and fiery political rhetoric may just lead an already confused person to engage in behaviors that produce unfortunate results. Consequently, it makes sense to be mindful of our political commentaries -- paying close attention to our local political context. These are times when our pens and our speeches can be even more powerful and deadly than the guns that may have been used today! 

My prayer is that God will console the families whose loved one is gone from amongst us. Let today be your day of decision making -- choose your path: living in peace and harmony or in insecurity and discord!    

Let not our compatriotsÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ die in vain! Peace to all!
author: Joseph Saah Fallah

report:
They had it all carved out of Allen White play book, with camera ready to take pictures of the results. In as much as it is sad for any Liberia to lose their life, I am shock that some Liberia are still willing to put themselves in harmÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s way for rogue politicians. After fighting senselessly for 14 years, and leaving some of these same individuals amputated, while several others are now forgotten, I find it pathetic that some have not learn their lesson. Visit Liberia and you will see people fighting on every street corners. Even in the US, we are uncontrollable. These are some of the aftermath of a senseless civil war. CDC knew this was coming.

This is the difference between UPians and CDCians. No matter how we love our standard-bearer, there is no way she is going to send us in the streets for a futile cause. Some brand us as blind loyalist, which I find laughable. At least almost every UPian knows why they support UP or have some knowledge of what the Unity Party stands for; unlike the CDCians. I am yet to see a CDCians who can emphatically state CDCÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s position is social political issues. This party clearly does not have a platform but some still see them as a feasible alternative to the UP led administration. Now tell me who is the BLIND LOYALIST? IF you can root for a party that has no sense of direction, but makes empty promises, then you are not only blind but also lack logical reasoning.

report:
In difficult times like these, sober reflexions and tolerance are indisputable imperatives to the maintenance of peace and tranquillity. The need for mutual respect cannot also be overemphasised. It is in recognition of these facts that I am tempted to comment on the latest riot/demonstration which according to Reuters has resulted in the lost of at least one life.

I am not concerned about whatever inquest that will take place hereinafter to establish the cause(s) of the riot/demonstration as I do not have all the facts. However, based on my personal experiences of complexion of this nationÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s historical and political intricacies I can offer a comment without passing judgement on any particular person or organisation because I am not privy to all the facts. I therefore prefer to generalise in my contribution to the issue.

As a nation and a people, irrespective of religious, ethnic, ideological and or political orientation, we are indivisible Ã¢â‚¬â€œ at least thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s what we were taught. This is why the demise of one Liberia diminishes me and I tend to think that it also diminishes many other Liberia. 

All of a certain what we had hope would have been a peaceful elections have claimed the lives of several compatriots of ours. Democracy does not have to be violent and so quite unfortunately, the signs on the wall of time do not make good reading. We have again demonstrated to the world that we are incapable of holding our own in the comity of civilised nations when challenged to the battle of ideas. 

Because that what democracy is: being able to sell big ideas to the electorates and by so doing win their votes. And there is so much to sell to the people of Liberia and get elected. For example: 
1. Liberia is the only West African costal country that does not meet the EU third party import standard of seafood and molluscs.
2. Funds generated from the National Social Security and Welfare Corporation  are not being used to address homelessness neither is the National Housing Corporation has any meaning to the ordinary citizen
3. Liberia has never fulfil its allotted quota for the importation of selected fruits into the EU under the Lome Convention
4. There is no proven strategic agriculture programme to meet domestic food production neither is there any to take advantage of the vast  regional and global market opportunities that exist
5. Liberia no longer exports palm kernel as it did before the 1980s though that market is bigger today than at any time in history.

These are job creating, income and revenues generating opportunities that could bring in billions of dollars to the economy but not being exploited neither to say that the list is not exhausted. So there are big issues that could win elections and many flaws of the government that could be exploited. But all we hear is about personality, hate, threats and the other gutter politics from either side.

Rather than subscribing to brand of politics which has moulded the thinking of supporters, those seeking power could have done better by focusing on some big issues to win the vote of the people. Our trademark politics of hate, fear, violence and division is just unhelpful for national unity, peace and progress. It can only degenerate our democratic process to anarchy. More than most, we know the consequences of replacing democracy and the rule of law with violence and therefore need no reminding. No more Liberia man or woman, boy or girl deserves to lose his/her life in the name of democracy.  

This is why news that at least one of our fellow compatriots was killed by the police and alleged threat from the CDC to boycott the run off elections is unfortunate. There is no justification for the police to use live bullet on anybody. Leaders from various parties, especially CDC and UP, failed to diffuse tension from the onset when they chose to nickname one another derogatorily Ã¢â‚¬ËœMonkeyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ and Ã¢â‚¬ËœBaboonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.  But like many such incidents before, the story tend to twirl in endless narratives. This was meant to be a simple, peaceful democratic process designed to elect our leaders. It is therefore a betrayal not only of the aspirations of the Liberia people but also the wishes of our founding fathers. All the people desire of their leaders is a peaceful prosperous nation in which they can live and bequeath to their children and the unborn generations. This cannot be too much to ask. On the other hand, our founding fathers wishes could not have been simpler: They sought to evince to the world that the Blackman too is capable of democratic self governance and compliance to the rule of law, hence the establishment of the nation state.

When we Ã¢â‚¬â€œ especially those vying for power and or in position of trust Ã¢â‚¬â€œ fall short of upholding these aspirations, an written covenant with posterity, the living and the unborn is broken. Our leaders must take the moral high grounds by leading by examples. However, when the presidency of the republic of Liberia is won at the expense of the tears, blood and lives of Liberia, then the moral high grounds are lost because the presidency does not worth any Liberia life. 

In a bizarre way we are very efficient at making things difficult for ourselves and others. We have allowed a common democratic process to claim at least a valuable life. This situation was entirely avoidable but for the lack of mutual trust, respect and tolerance among politicians which has adversely infected their followers. This is a failure of leadership. So as the costs from this violent episode are being counted and the inquest begun, common sense demands that we all stay shy exacerbating the tension by exercising restraint and eschew the easy option of jumping to knee jerk reactions.  Zealousness motivated by sycophancy, politics and ideology in difficult times like these run the risk of being antidotes to national unity and peace. Hence, resisting the temptations of bitterness and hate is our challenge to overcome by clinging on to the bonds of nationalism and justice.
author: Fitzgerald Vinton

report:
I will say this today, tomorrow, and any other day. Yesterday again and again, words were thrown out to people to get on the street to protest (demonstrate). What are we demonstrating for? At what cost are we demonstrating? Will it bring goods into our lives? Will it make better things to happen to us? The answer is so much NO. This is the work of the devil. Real work of the devil I tell you. The only reason why these things happen and continue to happen is because we worship political leaders and men with money. We throw out ourselves into the street to sell our souls for these people. We give out our children to these people. Who is Ellen, George orWinstonTubman? They are people like you and me. The only difference is that at one point in time, God smile with them and blessed them. Who are they to tell you to go and died for them? Is it because we do not know where we come from? Where we are going? What we stand for? We forget things too fast. Let us all concentrate very well. Let us be focus. What we do today may have great impact on our lives and lives of our children.  Let us come together and be one. Let us learn to love and share the goodness of God. 
Let me be frank and tell people. Prices will never go down unless God wants it to go down. The world population is increasing everyday with many more mouths to be fed. Poverty is increasing all around us. Lot of things is bound to happen so let us be careful. 
Ellen is not my mother. We talked today and tomorrow and everyday creating Ellen over and over and again. Liberia created Ellen. They made Ellen. They went out to look for her. They yawn for her help.  Today, people sit and listen to the devil and say Ã¢â‚¬Å“She is a warlordÃ¢â‚¬Â. Two Sundays ago, Prophet T. B. Joshua, spoke on words being used by other against their friends and said that if we called a person by a word or name, we should be careful because that name may come upon us also. Who can tell me the difference between what Charles Taylor did and what happen yesterday? ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s the act of Rebellion. What were they rebelling for? What do they want? Where are they coming from? Where are they going? Be careful Liberia. Be very careful. We believe we know all and yet we know nothing.  
During the olden days, it was not bullet that was used to killed man. They stoned a man death. They used rocks and stoned him to death.  Modern days developed bullet because itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s faster and quicker yet can also be as long as it wants you to feel the pain. 
See George Weah. He was blessed to be a footballer. Why are you pushing him to be something else? We are also creating Ã¢â‚¬Å“a different Geroge WeahÃ¢â‚¬Â.  Where is WinstonTubman coming from? Again I say, if he could not save the lives of those students that were killed and raped by the Doe Government then what can he do now? Be careful Liberia because what a man has done before he can also do again and will always do again. Let us learn to love and share. Please Liberia. Please.

Joshua, spoke on words being used by other against their friends and said that if we called a person by a word or name, we should be careful because that name may come upon us also. Who can tell me the difference between what Charles Taylor did and what happen yesterday? ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s the act of Rebellion. What were they rebelling for? What do they want? Where are they coming from? Where are they going? Be careful Liberia. Be very careful. We believe we know all and yet we know nothing.  
During the olden days, it was not bullet that was used to killed man. They stoned a man death. They used rocks and stoned him to death.  Modern days developed bullet because itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s faster and quicker yet can also be as long as it wants you to feel the pain. 
See George Weah. He was blessed to be a footballer. Why are you pushing him to be something else? We are also creating Ã¢â‚¬Å“a different Geroge WeahÃ¢â‚¬Â.  Where is WinstonTubman coming from? Again I say, if he could not save the lives of those students that were killed and raped by the Doe Government then what can he do now? report:
Today we are entering a new era for our country and its people. Today we r voting not for a party, but a victory for all the people of Liberia.
We fought for years because somebody wasnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t the right leader for us, what did war bring to us? Destruction of the political, social, and educational structures. This undesirable condition has tended to serve as a disincentive to the growth of our stagnant economy and have undoubtedly had a negative and adverse impact on the country.
Let us put out head up today Liberia and look forward to the time when the power of Love will replace the Love of power. Then Our Country Mama Liberia will know and experience the blessings of peaceÃ¢â‚¬Â¦
What difference does it make to the dead, whether the mad destruction is wrought under the name of totalitarianism or the holy name of liberty and democracy?
Let us talk peace plsss!

report:
They had it all carved out of Allen White play book, with camera ready to take pictures of the results. In as much as it is sad for any Liberia to lose their life, I am shock that some Liberia are still willing to put themselves in harmÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s way for rogue politicians. After fighting senselessly for 14 years, and leaving some of these same individuals amputated, while several others are now forgotten, I find it pathetic that some have not learn their lesson. Visit Liberia and you will see people fighting on every street corners. Even in the US, we are uncontrollable. These are some of the aftermath of a senseless civil war. CDC knew this was coming.

This is the difference between UPians and CDCians. No matter how we love our standard-bearer, there is no way she is going to send us in the streets for a futile cause. Some brand us as blind loyalist, which I find laughable. At least almost every UPian knows why they support UP or have some knowledge of what the Unity Party stands for; unlike the CDCians. I am yet to see a CDCians who can emphatically state CDCÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s position is social political issues. This party clearly does not have a platform but some still see them as a feasible alternative to the UP led administration. Now tell me who is the BLIND LOYALIST? IF you can root for a party that has no sense of direction, but makes empty promises, then you are not only blind but also lack logical reasoning.

report:
In difficult times like these, sober reflexions and tolerance are indisputable imperatives to the maintenance of peace and tranquillity. The need for mutual respect cannot also be overemphasised. It is in recognition of these facts that I am tempted to comment on the latest riot/demonstration which according to Reuters has resulted in the lost of at least one life.

I am not concerned about whatever inquest that will take place hereinafter to establish the cause(s) of the riot/demonstration as I do not have all the facts. However, based on my personal experiences of complexion of this nationÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s historical and political intricacies I can offer a comment without passing judgement on any particular person or organisation because I am not privy to all the facts. I therefore prefer to generalise in my contribution to the issue.

As a nation and a people, irrespective of religious, ethnic, ideological and or political orientation, we are indivisible Ã¢â‚¬â€œ at least thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s what we were taught. This is why the demise of one Liberia diminishes me and I tend to think that it also diminishes many other Liberia. 

All of a certain what we had hope would have been a peaceful elections have claimed the lives of several compatriots of ours. Democracy does not have to be violent and so quite unfortunately, the signs on the wall of time do not make good reading. We have again demonstrated to the world that we are incapable of holding our own in the comity of civilised nations when challenged to the battle of ideas. 

Because that what democracy is: being able to sell big ideas to the electorates and by so doing win their votes. And there is so much to sell to the people of Liberia and get elected. For example: 
1. Liberia is the only West African costal country that does not meet the EU third party import standard of seafood and molluscs.
2. Funds generated from the National Social Security and Welfare Corporation  are not being used to address homelessness neither is the National Housing Corporation has any meaning to the ordinary citizen
3. Liberia has never fulfil its allotted quota for the importation of selected fruits into the EU under the Lome Convention
4. There is no proven strategic agriculture programme to meet domestic food production neither is there any to take advantage of the vast  regional and global market opportunities that exist
5. Liberia no longer exports palm kernel as it did before the 1980s though that market is bigger today than at any time in history.

These are job creating, income and revenues generating opportunities that could bring in billions of dollars to the economy but not being exploited neither to say that the list is not exhausted. So there are big issues that could win elections and many flaws of the government that could be exploited. But all we hear is about personality, hate, threats and the other gutter politics from either side.

Rather than subscribing to brand of politics which has moulded the thinking of supporters, those seeking power could have done better by focusing on some big issues to win the vote of the people. Our trademark politics of hate, fear, violence and division is just unhelpful for national unity, peace and progress. It can only degenerate our democratic process to anarchy. More than most, we know the consequences of replacing democracy and the rule of law with violence and therefore need no reminding. No more Liberia man or woman, boy or girl deserves to lose his/her life in the name of democracy.  

This is why news that at least one of our fellow compatriots was killed by the police and alleged threat from the CDC to boycott the run off elections is unfortunate. There is no justification for the police to use live bullet on anybody. Leaders from various parties, especially CDC and UP, failed to diffuse tension from the onset when they chose to nickname one another derogatorily Ã¢â‚¬ËœMonkeyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ and Ã¢â‚¬ËœBaboonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.  But like many such incidents before, the story tend to twirl in endless narratives. This was meant to be a simple, peaceful democratic process designed to elect our leaders. It is therefore a betrayal not only of the aspirations of the Liberia people but also the wishes of our founding fathers. All the people desire of their leaders is a peaceful prosperous nation in which they can live and bequeath to their children and the unborn generations. This cannot be too much to ask. On the other hand, our founding fathers wishes could not have been simpler: They sought to evince to the world that the Blackman too is capable of democratic self governance and compliance to the rule of law, hence the establishment of the nation state.

When we Ã¢â‚¬â€œ especially those vying for power and or in position of trust Ã¢â‚¬â€œ fall short of upholding these aspirations, an written covenant with posterity, the living and the unborn is broken. Our leaders must take the moral high grounds by leading by examples. However, when the presidency of the republic of Liberia is won at the expense of the tears, blood and lives of Liberia, then the moral high grounds are lost because the presidency does not worth any Liberia life. 

In a bizarre way we are very efficient at making things difficult for ourselves and others. We have allowed a common democratic process to claim at least a valuable life. This situation was entirely avoidable but for the lack of mutual trust, respect and tolerance among politicians which has adversely infected their followers. This is a failure of leadership. So as the costs from this violent episode are being counted and the inquest begun, common sense demands that we all stay shy exacerbating the tension by exercising restraint and eschew the easy option of jumping to knee jerk reactions.  Zealousness motivated by sycophancy, politics and ideology in difficult times like these run the risk of being antidotes to national unity and peace. Hence, resisting the temptations of bitterness and hate is our challenge to overcome by clinging on to the bonds of nationalism and justice.

report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman

I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman

report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman

report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman

report:
All the ringleaders and the so called messengers of boycotting need to be arrested.  TheyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve been threatening people all week, telling us not to go out, and if we do something will happen.  They had no intentions to march yesterday.  Many of the Ã¢â‚¬Å“ringleadersÃ¢â‚¬Â were home or about, and nowhere near CDC headquarters, where there incident took place.  They wanted to cause this madness in hopes that the election wouldn't happen today.  This has been their strategy all along.  I hope the government and the international community take this seriously by arresting and prosecuting the ones who plan the march without obtaining a permit.  Liberia has LAWS!  We are governed by a Constitution.  Why would any sensible person decide to organize a Ã¢â‚¬Å“marchÃ¢â‚¬Â without a permit?  One day prior to a runoff they are boycotting?  Because of the hunger for power by a few, a young man is dead!!! And of course they are now shifting the blame to UPÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ UP organized several rallies throughout Liberia; no one was hurt or killed.  You can claim Ã¢â‚¬Å“peacefulÃ¢â‚¬Â all you want, and your ACTIONS speaks otherwise.  Why the gas station???

And for the idiots who doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know what a peaceful demonstration is, let me tell you:  1.  It means following the law, getting a damn permit, 2.  it means not throwing rocks at the police (armed police, teargas, guns or rotten).

report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman

report: Actually Rob Dorley, as a Liberia who happens to be a lawyer and lives in the US right now, I can assure that the authorities would do the same, if not more, in the US. Usually, they even get a warrant to search one's home, job, etc. Here, individuals are routinely arrested for threats against the Pres., and against public safety. Freedom of speech/movement is NOT an absolute right in that the state has a greater interest/responsibility, in maintaining order and civility.Arrests are made for having no permits, individuals beaten, etc. (ie, some of current problems with the Occupy Wall Street mov't or previous civil rights demonstrations).Police brutality, esp. against minorities, is as common as the sunrise in most urban areas, especially against black men. When you put the events in Liberia into context, wherein you have leaders on the air making inflammatory/misleading statements that could incite riots or disturb the peace, the gov't can ask the courts for permission to temporarily shut down those media outlets to prevent unrest, until order is restored. No one in the US can go on nat'l radio, especially the night before the presidential elections, and say anything that could intimidate the public from voting or suggest that the gov't is against the populace. Are you kidding me? The FBI would be at their door in a minute. And yes, airports and bus terminals would be alerted once a warrant is gotten. Gov'ts learned this the hard way from the Rwanda example. So don't let the textbooks romanticize democracy as giving absolute rights. By the way, you do realize the US still executes people and has not been a signatory to some torture conventions, etc.
author: Bindu Padmore Wotorson

When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."

report: Because I went to law school. Are you kidding me? The issue would be "whether" the court was right in granting such a warrant, based on facts/ precedent, etc. But whether the gov't has right to prevent unrest is inherent. It doesn't happen in the US because this is a MATURE democracy hundreds of years old that's had time to practice order without interruption since its civil war. Ours is essentially 6yrs old in terms of freedom of press, multiple party elections, etc. So there are now things, Americans just don't do that we in developing countries still do... not because we're backwards, etc. but simply because we still young democracies LEARNING HOW to practice democracy.

report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman

report: Offie Bright, your right to free speech does not mean you can yell "Fire!" in a crowded theater. There was a riot yesterday with one confirmed death. The city was on edge and you have a media house giving space for comments that have the propensity to exacerbate an already volatile situation. I've read your comments on here where you ask people if "they were there yesterday?" You were here a couple of weeks ago when Acarous Gray called in to a radio program to say that SSS, Police and NSA had surrounded his house to arrest him. CDC partisans came out supposedly to protect him. What do you think would have happened yesterday if they had continued to talk about an "assassination list? You are a private citizen and are entitled to your view. Nobody would hold you accountable should the state unravel. We would hold the Justice Minister accountable. She did the prudent thing.

report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman

report: The closure of media institutions is press censorship and has got no place in democracy. There can be no justification for the government shutting down Power Fm, Love Fm and Kings Fm. Liberia is gradually returning to its ugly past and nobody seems to care. Almost everybody is adoring this undemocratic act by theEllenJohnsonSirleaf administration without considering the corresponding consequences. Only dictators can muscle the press and shut independent radio stations. The other day ellen sacked LBS boss becasue he allowed an opposition to hold alive press conference on the state radio. Today, ellen has shut down three independent radio stations. I have always argued that Liberia did no go to war because there was no light, water, better living, etc. The same things that are now creeping were responsible for our civil war. The country is threading the path of war under the watchful eyes of ellen. Does anybody care?

report: Offie, c'mon we're going through an analysis about what the LAW should/shouldn't allow. We're discussing media censorship...that's a basic element of freedom of speech in Liberia. That's part of the Liberia constitution--the same constitution modeled after the US (three branches of gov't, etc. just like that democracy). So to deny that is to not acknowledge on what principles your country was founded. You can rarely find two exact situations in history (US vote boycott) but you do have similar lessons/precedent and that's what makes this discussion focus less on the exact facts but on the past lessons learned and the law relating to freedom of speech. In the past, in Liberia, like during the Doe years, warrants often weren't first gotten. And in the US, there was a time in the 1800's- early 1900's, the same issues occurred. Over time, the rule of law was respected. So when I see that court orders are first gotten in Liberia, in accordance with Liberia law, that's huge...more progress than young Liberia may realize. And btw, the US is often compared to England, France,etc. Most of those are actually socialist gov'ts but the right to vote is extremely cherished in those socieities. Yes, nations are sovereign but none exists in a bubble so when you're trying to develop yours, you have to explore what works best in other societies and what parts of those societies you'll emulate and what parts you won't based on your own national priorities/culture.

report:
Fellow Liberia Ã¢â‚¬â€œ I believe that, regardless of our differences in opinion on who the next President of our country should be, we all would agree that the happenings of yesterday was (1) very saddening, (2) puts a mark on this country that we do not want, and (3) stemmed from issues far greater than the elections itself. Now, we can go on and on about the perceived fraud, or lack thereof, of the elections process, but is that REALLY the issue??? I, for one, believe that that there are much greater underlying issues. Although, the elections are the central point of this forum, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d like to put that aside for just a minute. Is it conceivable that we could all, as Liberia, focus on the actual ISSUES that we have with the Government. In doing so, letÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s keep a couple of real facts in mind. (1) Elections are being held today (2)The results of the elections will be announced (3) The winner will be inaugurated as President in January and (4) The President will be the only leader of this country (unless we are hell bent on destruction).

For anyone who disagrees with these facts, you should probably stop reading now because this exercise is not going to help you or any of us. For those who accept these facts and want to move forward, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d like us to take some time and think logically about the next steps before answering this question. 

IF YOU COULD MAKE A SUBSTANTIVE CHANGE IN THE WAY THE GOVERNMENT IS DEALING WITH AN ISSUE, WHAT WOULD THAT ISSUE BE AND HOW WOULD YOU GO ABOUT MAKING THAT CHANGE? For this exercise to really work, we must remember the HOW part of the question. It is very easy to voice the WHAT, but until we start dealing with the HOW we will go NOWHERE. Let's get UNSTUCK!
author: Wadei Powell

report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman
