report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."
author: Barkue Tubman

report: E BillWinstonTubman, I'd hope that your gift doesn't stop at recognizing "google lawyers". You're not supposed to make sweeping statements about things you barely understand. Even UNMIL which had police officers deployed on the scene has not issued a definitive statement about what transpired. There were reports that gunfire came from the fence. We don't know if it is true. There are eyewitness reports that somebody other than the police fired at least three shots on the hill overlooking the party headquarters. None of this is verified. It is therefore strange, non-google lawyer that you are, you would be making claims about violated rights on the eve of the election. On Saturday the President gave a speech calling the 'boycott" unconstitutional. On Monday the NEC issued a statement saying there was no statutory or legal provision for a political party to withdraw from the process at this point - making any such withdrawal illegal. I didn't see one post from you about the constitutionality. All of a sudden you've become a non-google constitutional lawyer. Please.

Today we are entering a new era for our country and its people. Today we r voting not for a party, but a victory for all the people of Liberia.
We fought for years because somebody wasnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t the right leader for us, what did war bring to us? Destruction of the political, social, and educational structures. This undesirable condition has tended to serve as a disincentive to the growth of our stagnant economy and have undoubtedly had a negative and adverse impact on the country.
Let us put out head up today Liberia and look forward to the time when the power of Love will replace the Love of power. Then Our Country Mama Liberia will know and experience the blessings of peaceÃ¢â‚¬Â¦
What difference does it make to the dead, whether the mad destruction is wrought under the name of totalitarianism or the holy name of liberty and democracy?

report:
just curious about your views on this:  A CDC member who just won a representative seat during the 1st round of elections sent this... what are your thoughts:  
"Hello my dear friends, I am so worried! Is this how we will live in Liberia? I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I was stopped from boarding the plane today. I was travelling to Ghana on the Kenya Airways 5pm flight but to my absolute disappointment, my right to free movement was abused. I say this to say, I was told by one Mr. Forkpah an officer of the Bureau of Immigration that the Minister of Justice Cllr. Christina Tah has ordered my arrest and that I Munah E. Pelham is wanted and so I cannot leave the country. My dear Liberia, my passport was taken away from me and I was not allowed on board the plane. When I asked Ã¢â‚¬Å“why am I wanted?Ã¢â‚¬Â The officer said it was an order that no one from CDC (my political Party) should leave the country. My reply was why? But no answer. He later said, I should call some top government security officials if I really want to leave. So I did. I was able to talk to the Defense Minister, Commissioner Williams of Immigration, Minister Piah of the Ministry of Information and many others in authority not forgetting the Immigration Commissioner himself Hon. Massaquoi who I called almost 30 times but he refused to answer me. I tried so hard to find out what was going on and why I was not allowed to leave the country but none of them could tell me. When I asked to get my passport back, Mr. Forkpah the immigration officer told me to pick it up from the Ministry of Justice. So I returned to Monrovia without my passport. Now what next? Is this how we are going to lead our people? Can someone please advice...............cuz I certainly want to talk to my Lawyer about issues like, My ticket fares, hotel bill that was paid in Ghana, other expenses in getting ready for this all important business trip."

report: wait, wait...hold on, lets be fair.  not all members of CDC are evil people out to destroy Liberia.  I think we have to take that notion from our minds that if somebody is a member of CDC they must be evil, ignorant and not capable of being patriotic citizens. Its the same as saying everybody from the Middle East must be terrorists.  As far as I know, Liberia has not declared a state of emergency, nor has the government announced that all leaders of CDC are wanted for questioning, nor has their been an announcement made that travel of CDC members are banned.   The best intentions of a government comes into question when it starts to look like things are being done under cover.   If there is a security threat and the government wants to ban CDCians from traveling or wants to question them, then it needs to be made public and the proper and lawful procedures should be put in place.      This young woman is first and foremost a Liberia citizens who has equal rights under our constitution.   I believe her travel should be restricted only if she is thought to have committed a criminal offence, but not just because she is a member of a political party.

report:
WE DONÃ¢â‚¬ÂT WANT WAR AGAIN IN LIBERIA

After five years of beginning to experience what a taste of democracy, education, freedom, and   social equality feel like for this generation, the political leaders of old, today stand at the threshold of a new dawn determining again the future of millions of young Liberia, who for the past 21 years have being stripped of their dignity, cognitive and human rights, education, and liberty.  The impact of what happened yesterday is a revelatory expression that shows the failure of the old bureaucratic political leadership practices by previous generation: putting power, self-aggrandizement, and popularity ahead of people.   Let us not ignore this reality because it has the potential again to degenerate into another repercussion that disenfranchises and cripples the young generation from being potent and erudite to lead the future of Liberia.  Yesterday was a suitable moment for presidential candidates (UP &CDC) to have spoken a mandate of peace and calm under-girded by non-violence; rather they watch the eve of a peaceful historical moment turned into a violent scenario.  Prime Minister, Benjamin Disraeli, once said, Ã¢â‚¬Å“I must follow the people. Am I not their leader?Ã¢â‚¬Â (ChangingMinds.org). This to me is the true characteristic of leadersÃ¢â‚¬â€having the desire to lead but doing so by the auspices of the Liberia people and their interest. Whatever the condition was yesterday, change does not come about through violence, if it does, than our history of violence should have delivered to us a lasting change. Change I believe comes by employing a non-violence protest sustained by self-respect and self-controlÃ¢â‚¬â€it is what Dr. Martin Luther King called Ã¢â‚¬Å“creative protestÃ¢â‚¬Â (disengaged from physical violence).

Today marks another dayÃ¢â‚¬â€whatever the differences are, the young Liberia are not prepare for another act of violence, as evident by the respond of the young people who  turn out today to exercise their rights  to vote. This I believe is a message to political leaders in Liberia, who are still romanticized by the rhetoric of the antiquated political constructÃ¢â‚¬â€that resort to power greed and violence as a mean.  This message is clear and simple, captivating the attentions of the international communities, especially Liberia youth around the world: We donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t want war again in our country. While we are praying for the best outcome, we are also strategic that any fatal attempt to jeopardize the future of young people in Liberia, will resolve into a large scale of non-violence protect and advocacy in Liberia with a clear intention-- fuel by technological networking and the media attention around the world.  We have learned the most democratic and creative intervention for change in Africa, from Egypt and TunisiaÃ¢â‚¬â€and we are prepared to take this step (creative technological protest) for the betterment of change and democracy.  We call on all Liberia, concern advocates, and institutions around the world to get ready and be alert to network and provide resources to foster a cost of Change and Freedom for Liberia because --WE DONÃ¢â‚¬â„¢T WANT WAR  AGAIN IN LIBERIA.

report:
Aljazeera online news: "Around 4,500 polling stations have opened in Liberia's presidential  run-off election amid fears of violence and intimidation after clashes  left at least four people dead in the capital, Monrovia.Al  Jazeera's correspondent Yvonne Ndege, reporting from Monrovia, said on  Tuesday that the quiet atmosphere around the polling stations "might be  one of the side effects of the violence and chaos around the streets of  Monrovia yesterday.
There is a sense that people are afraid to come out and vote and this could naturally have an impact on turnout.The  opposition is calling for protests today and asking their supporters to  wear black, and are calling today a funeral for democracy in Liberia."  our correspondent said.Meanwhile human rights group Amnesty  International (AI) on Tuesday urged police and all Liberia political  candidates to act to stop the election related violence and prevent  further bloodshed andÃ‚Â recommended an independent and impartial  investigation into possible human rights abuses during the election  period.Carolyn Norris,Ã‚Â Amnesty InternationalÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s deputy director  for Africa, said in a press statement that politicians and police need  to demonstrate that their main concern is protecting lives" after deadly  clashes erupted between police and opposition supporters on Monday.
Demonstrators had taken to the streets  after WinstonTubman, the opposition candidate hoping to unseat Ellen  EllenJohnsonSirleaf, said he would boycott the run-off and called on his  supporters to do likewise over fears of fraud favouring the incumbent  president."

report: One day I am a UP sympathizers, the next day I am a Cidian. Well, that's human nature and it is pointless to respond to all this. The fact remains, that as journalists and in the line of work we do, there are no permanent friends. We will work to the dictates of our conscience, plain simple.This site was created bearing in mind that differences will ensue but that in all this, we must show respect and muster the spirit to dialogue constructively. Remember, when we posted UP campaign rallies in three counties in straight succession, CDC guys said we were biased. When we covered Brumskine rally at the ATS, people said it was done to deliberately shame the Brumskine turnout. When we cover the CDC rally, some folks said we give them more space and coverage. Just when we were releasing our monitoring report, portions that dealt with Truth FM was rejected by people aligned with UP, whereas sections dealing with the shortfalls of Love and Kings FM were overlooked.  When we presented our initial account of the Nov. 7 CDC riot most UP sympathizers commended the update but when we brought photo details, we are having to face their court of law.Now the State has illegally close down three radio stations in Liberia, we are being dammed because we choose not to be silent. An interesting dilemma, you may conjecture. We will do our jobs. We will report objectively and we will do this bearing in mind that Liberia is the one place we have and no where else. What matters ultimately is the truth and the truth we will stand by. In few hours, we will release preliminary results on our site from the second round of coverage of the elections- a work that earned us bad branding from CDC supporters and the AfricanStandard Online Newspaper. At the time, we were VERY Objective in the eyes of UP supporters and biased in the eyes of CDC. Follow the results and enjoy the Run-off. This too is Liberia....www.lmcliberia.com

report:
The events that unfolded in Liberia yesterday are heart breaking and disconcerting. When Fwww.frontpageafrica.com alerted Liberia of Weah and Alan WhiteÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s plan to hijack the country, skeptics said it was another ploy to create fear amongst the citizenry. Between June 2010 and October 2011, we have seen caches of arms and ammunitions being discovered and ceased in Grand Gedeh County near the Ivori...an border, Nimba County as well as River Gee County and near the Liberia/Sierra Leonean border. If these trends did not send a message to the Liberia people, then we probably are all asleep. Quite recently,WinstonTubman had an interview with Reuters news and warned of chaos in Liberia and the sub-region if the run-of elections were not called off. Who the hell does he think he is?WinstonTubman failed miserably as Head of the United Nations Mission in Somalia and wants Liberia to be ungovernable as Somalia. The waves of violence by CDC are well calculated and as such, drastic actions should be taken againstWinstonTubman, Weah and their group of hooligans. Liberia should not sit supinely and allow CDC to incite violence and threaten the young democracy that we are trying to nurture and sustain. While I sympathize with those who lost loved ones during the fracas I do support the proactive stance of the Police in protecting lives and properties. Why were the United Nations vehicles vandalized? Why was George KailondoÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s business ransacked and looted? I saw this coming when those gross ignoramuses (CDCians), uncompromising bigots and butt heads viciously attacked Eugene NagbeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s home and cars. We cannot allow this to continue. Could this have happened under Master Sergeant Samuel K. Doe or Charles Ghankay Taylor? Thanks immensely to all peace loving and well-meaning Liberia who turned out and exercised their vote without fear. Under no condition will we revert to the brutal and uncivilized past that our country had to endure. In union strong success is sure we cannot fail. Forward ever and backward never! God bless Liberia!

The waves of violence by CDC are well calculated and as such, drastic actions should be taken againstWinstonTubman, Weah and their group of hooligans. Liberia should not sit supinely and allow CDC to incite violence and threaten the young democracy that we are trying to nurture and sustain. While I sympathize with those who lost loved ones during the fracas I do  support the proactive stance of the Police in protecting lives and properties. Why were the United Nations vehicles vandalized? Why was George KailondoÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s business ransacked and looted? I saw this coming when those gross ignoramuses (CDCians), uncompromising bigots and butt heads viciously attacked Eugene NagbeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s home and cars. We cannot allow this to continue. Could this have happened under Master Sergeant Samuel K. Doe or Charles Ghankay Taylor? Thanks immensely to all peace loving and well-meaning Liberia who turned out and exercised their vote without fear. Under no condition will we revert to the brutal and uncivilized past that our country had to endure. In union strong success is sure we cannot fail. Forward ever  and backward never! God bless Liberia!

report: You are right. When you have little to lose, you take more risks. I recently was read the President's job plan for the next six years and it included a reasonable number of new jobs promised over the next 6yrs.Reasonable if one compared the number of corporations coming into the country with their employee needs. Reasonable in that infrastructural plans for roads and bridges could use this kind of unskilled labor, etc. Because all industries were destroyed during the war and we had unskilled labor and no investors, plus foreign debt, it has taken these first 6 yrs just to get to point of attracting investors and rebuilding basic industries.Also our political instability continues to frighten off even Liberia entrepreneurs in the diaspora who may employ many of the youth. Development is slow but the jobs will trickle in at several thousands a year, as long as there's peace. With such a large youth population, it will be difficult for all the youth to find work immediately. So some will have to go to the community colleges planned in each county, get vocational training, etc. and be given some purpose that leads them into employment.Rebuilding a failed, broken state is not an easy task.I don't envy EJS but most of her initiatives over the last 6 yrs and for the next administration seem progressive enough.

report: Mr. Kpargoi, it is simple. Allegations of fraud were infinitesimal and not widespread. The Liberia elections like elections everywhere are always plagued with incidents of irregularities. Al Gore reportedly won the elections in the United States, but the Presidency was given to George W. Bush. The US Supreme Court ruled and determined that the level of irregularities did not warrant an overturn of the results. Americans did not destroy their country or engage in hostilities. The United Nations, European Union, African Union, Carter Center, ECOWAS and other bodies monitored the Liberia elections and deemed it to free, fair and transparent.

report: Bro, I live in a democracy and we AM radio stations her that have 20 million listeners a week, and all the preach is hate, racism and ish about  the president and the government. If Liberia wants to practice democracy, it has to practice it the whole 9-yards. And as I write this note, those AM radio stations are on and alive 24/7, from one presenter to the other, around the clock. No one closes down radio station in a democracy. Deal with the individual who says things that might deemed a breach of his license. Journalists do not own their responsibilities to the government, unless of course they work for the government. The responsible they owe to the people and their listeners is provide them with adequate information. Depending on who they broadcast to (who's tuning in to them or reading their version of things), those are whom they owe responsibilities to. We have to move up! It's time you as a consumer selects what is it that's good for your ears. Every radio or TV station does not owe an allegiance to everybody.

report: Jack Kanneh Bro, I live in a democracy, and we have AM radio stations and daily newspapers here with 20 million listeners or readerships a week, and all they preach is hate, racism and ish about the president, the government, blacks, gays, etc. If Liberia wants to practice democracy, it has to practice it the whole 9-yards. And as I write this note, those AM radio stations are on and alive 24/7, from one presenter to the other, around the clock. No one closes down radio station in a democracy. Deal with the individual who says things that might be deemed a breach of his license. Journalists do not owe their responsibilities to the government, unless of course they work for the government. The responsibility they owe is to the their listeners and customers. if the radio is preaching hates you dislike, rally her listeners to move their advertising dollars to a better radio/TV that's in line with your views. It's a business, not a charity. Depending on who they broadcast to (who's tuning in to them or reading their version of things), those are whom they owe responsibilities to. We have to move up! It's time you, as a consumer selects what is it that's good for your ears. Every radio or TV station does not owe an allegiance to everybody. Period.

report: I feel bad when everyone in Liberia wants to condemne and make derogatory comments about journalism and journalists in the country. Our journalists are doing very well given the circumstances and environment in which they work. In Liberia, journalist who do not broadcast or report what the priviledged public want to hear or read, are branded most times as not being professional journalists. In journalism, everyone needs to be heard; everyone's story needs to be told. If journalist or media institution were on Monday only reporting what the government or it's sympathizers wanted to hear, how were we going to know that there were fatalities and injuries. I read many comments on postings trying to justify the closure of media institutions in the aftermath of the Monday incident, and otherwise questioning the professionalism of journalists and media institutions. But GOL did not have to use well armed police to enforce the closure of the Radio and TV stations, if it is true that there was a court order. Where were the court officers? Why do we use the guns to intimidate unarmed citizens? Most of you always say the journalist has not reported a balanced story when your side is not explained.  Granted.This government is gradually incresing it's abuse record despite the gains made so far. It is under obligation to be tolerant with the freedoms it is accepting. May be PresidentEllenJohnsonSirleaf did not know what happened. I can therefore imagine how embarrased she was when she heard about the proceedure used to shut down those stations. Because continuous closure of those institutions is not healthy for her gains. When she used to be on the run, it was the Liberia Press that took risks to aid her escapes from Presidents Doe and Taylor. Many times she invited Journalists to secret locations where she made statements daring to those administrations and told journalist to embargo until she left the country. It was the Liberia journalists who made her and popularized the "Iron Lady" name that the whole world knows. Let us remember that doing the wrong thing wronly or doing the wrong thing rightly, does not still make it right. So please stop blaming the journalists.

Hey guys, I just remember this one. You remember I told you guys are was driving for someone before and and how I lost my driving job? This heppened to me one night when I was still their driver.
I was going home one night/morning around 1.00am alone in my bossman car, I got to a check point.The policeman stopped me and asked for everything which I gave out. The I replied: I'm not alone, Jesus Christ is with me here, Angel Gabriel, Angel Rapheal, Angel Micheal and five angels are with me here.
The policeman said: "all these people inside this your small car? I charge you for overloading!!!
I had to pay that guy 25 ghana cedis that night.
My small money Madam just give me after doing her overtime went to that police man

report: I hear people saying "more need to be done". Pray tell me what this "more" is? I think Bindu's comment here is logical and objective. Where would these jobs come from? I know a lot of young people who'd rather sit at home and do nothing because wages are too low. When I joined the GOL back in 2006 a lot of my friends mocked at me for working from 9a-10p for a $2500ld pay check initially when they would just sit at home and get far more than I made as a skilled worker. The industries that are now hiring employs over 80% of young qualified workers. Unskilled workers are also hired short term for govt projects, there are young professional programs in country, there are internship programs, young people are recruited and trained for all major govt events, etc. And like Bindu said the impact we need to see are not immediate--they're long term. Young people should also make use of themselves by starting small businesses. I know a lot who have and this has kept them busy, focused and out of trouble. The government has not done Everything but it has put in place the policies and made the efforts that any forward thinking institution would make. As we say, "house was not built in one day."

report:
Cyrus W Badio wrote:
REPUBLIC OF LIBERIA
EXECUTIVE MANSION
MONROVIA, LIBERIA
________________________________________

Office of the Press Secretary to the President

PRESS RELEASE

(MONROVIA, LIBERIA - November 8, 2011): President EllenJohnsonSirleaf has expressed deep sorrow and regret over the violence which resulted in the death, Monday, at the headquarters of the opposition, Congress for Democratic Change (CDC). The President said an investigation is currently being conducted, promising that perpetrators will be brought to justice.

An Executive Mansion release says the Liberia leader was speaking to reporters, Tuesday, in Fefeh town, Bomi County, where she had travelled to  cast her vote in Presidential run-off election taking place throughout the country.

The President noted that she was pleased with the peaceful conduct of the process and said she was hopeful that, following the election, the country  will move forward. The President said she believes that Liberia will find a way to move forward, heal the wounds and reconcile their difference. 

"I think Liberia want peace, they want their basic needs met, and that will be our obligation and our commitment," the President emphasized.

Commenting on the mood of the country in the months leading to 
inauguration, the President said Liberia will continue to go about their business in a peaceful atmosphere, and predicted a bright future for the country.

Signed: _________________________

 Cyrus Wleh Badio

Press Secretary to the President

report: Mr. Moore, I was in Liberia four months ago and the number one thing I heard my fellow youths say to me was the lack of capital to start their own ventures. The govt can act as an "enabler" by housing a youth- focused micro finance fund within the micro finance department at the central bank. I know you will quickly cry, but what about MFI operating in Liberia? Well, the data shows that over 90% of their capital is lent to women, typically head of households. Another tangible solution, create a state-owned bank or credit facility for Small & Medium sized Enterprises ( SME). It is a known fact that the banks in Liberia are more prone to lend to established businesses with credible track record than SMEs, who are the back bone of most economies. Just a few, hope these quench your specificity thirst!

By Richard Valdmanis and Alphonso Toweh
MONROVIA | Tue Nov 8, 2011 3:27pm EST
(Reuters) - Many Liberia failed to vote in a presidential run-off on Tuesday, poll observers said, some people staying away for fear of further violence and others following an opposition boycott appeal.

Voters trickled into polling stations in the capital Monrovia in much lower numbers than the first round vote last month, Reuters witnesses said. Feedback from elsewhere in the West African state also put turnout down by late-afternoon.

Incumbent EllenJohnsonSirleaf is tipped to win re-election after leading the first round vote, and because second placed challenger WinstonTubman has withdrawn from the contest citing electoral fraud.

But a low turnout risks harmingEllenJohnsonSirleaf's authority in a new term despite international praise for the new Nobel peace laureate and broad condemnation ofWinstonTubman's boycott call.

United Nations peacekeepers were deployed, but the streets of the capital were quiet after a day of clashes that officials say killed at least two.

"People are taking a long time to come because of the situation of yesterday. There is fear in the voters," said Mitchell Gbarteah, an election worker in Monrovia's West Point, a slum of tin and wood hovels.

Officials from two observer groups said low numbers were also being reported by colleagues country-wide.

"We have spoken to our observers across the country and the indication that we are getting is that turnout is very low," said Dan Saryee, head of the Liberia Democratic Institute, which is tracking the vote.

"If it continues the way it is going now, I can safely say that turnout will be 25-35 percent," he said. In the Oct 11 first round vote, turnout was more than 71 percent.

The poll is the first locally-organised presidential election since a civil war ended in 2003. It is expected to pave the way for new investment, but fears are rising it could instead usher in open-ended political turmoil.

On one street corner in the crumbling coastal capital, a group of two dozen young men stood discussing politics.

"I will never vote, the government has stacked things massively against us ... They came in there shooting, not just teargas, at harmless people" said Anthony Korvayan, 28.

On Monday, police fired tear gas to disperse hundreds ofWinstonTubman's supporters and officers also fired live rounds when they stormedWinstonTubman's CDC party headquarters. [ID:nL6E7M726J]

But, standing next to Korvayan, Benedict Hena held up an ink-stained finger, and said he had voted: "It is our right."

U.S. President Barack Obama called on Liberia security forces to show restraint and allow peaceful protest, and he warned against any voting violations. [ID:nN1E7A622S]

"The international community will hold accountable those who choose to obstruct the democratic process," he said.

Two radio stations seen to supportWinstonTubman and running mate and former football star George Weah, were shut down overnight.

After voting in Fefee, her home town just outside Monrovia,EllenJohnsonSirleaf sought to dampen tensions, saying she regretted the loss of life and promised an investigation.

"Liberia is going to move forward. We will find a way to heal the wounds. We will also find a way to reconcile people," she said, vowing to make youth a priority of her mandate.

However,WinstonTubman, a former U.N. ambassador, accused the president of using "violence against peaceful people." On Tuesday he remained vague on his next move. "We will boycott today and wait and see how that pans out."

Liberia is one of the world's poorest countries and some 14 years of war killed nearly 250,000 and left its infrastructure in ruins.

"DON'T WANT TROUBLE"

Johnson-Sirleaf -- whose standing at home, where many complain improvements have come too slowly, is not always on a par with international praise for the recently-named Nobel Peace Prize winner -- won nearly 44 percent of the first round vote.

She has since secured the backing of the third-placed finisher, former warlord Prince Johnson.

Tubman, who won about 33 percent in the first round , has alleged three ballot boxes were tampered with and said he would only participate in a run-off if it were delayed by two to four weeks and if counting procedures were amended.

The October 11 first round was broadly accepted by international observers and regional bodies have criticizedWinstonTubman's boycott decision.

Yet many of his supporters are unemployed former fighters and, while it is too early to be sure of turnout, analysts warned a successful boycott would complicate the incumbent's next mandate, perhaps forcing her into dialogue withWinstonTubman.

"Instead of consolidation and construction, it will be a second mandate of justification and possibly power-sharing," said Lydie Boka, head of risk consultancy StrategiCo.

Liberia's iron ore and oil have already attracted major firms including ArcelorMittal, BHP Billiton and Anadarko Petroleum and a smooth poll could entice more.

Many in Liberia are just hoping for peace.

"We don't want any trouble. But monkey and baboon not getting along," said a Monrovia resident who called himself Tarr, using the nicknames Liberia have given the candidates.

(Additional reporting by Claire MacDougall; Writing by David Lewis; Editing by Giles Elgood and Matthew Jones)

But a low turnout risks harmingEllenJohnsonSirleaf's authority in a new term despite international praise for the new Nobel peace laureate and broad condemnation ofWinstonTubman's boycott call.

United Nations peacekeepers were deployed, but the streets of the capital were quiet after a day of clashes that officials say killed at least two.

"People are taking a long time to come because of the situation of yesterday. There is fear in the voters," said Mitchell Gbarteah, an election worker in Monrovia's West Point, a slum of tin and wood hovels.

Officials from two observer groups said low numbers were also being reported by colleagues country-wide.

"We have spoken to our observers across the country and the indication that we are getting is that turnout is very low," said Dan Saryee, head of the Liberia Democratic Institute, which is tracking the vote.

"If it continues the way it is going now, I can safely say that turnout will be 25-35 percent," he said. In the Oct 11 first round vote, turnout was more than 71 percent.

The poll is the first locally-organised presidential election since a civil war ended in 2003. It is expected to pave the way for new investment, but fears are rising it could instead usher in open-ended political turmoil.

On one street corner in the crumbling coastal capital, a group of two dozen young men stood discussing politics.

"I will never vote, the government has stacked things massively against us ... They came in there shooting, not just teargas, at harmless people" said Anthony Korvayan, 28.

On Monday, police fired tear gas to disperse hundreds ofWinstonTubman's supporters and officers also fired live rounds when they stormedWinstonTubman's CDC party headquarters. [ID:nL6E7M726J]

But, standing next to Korvayan, Benedict Hena held up an ink-stained finger, and said he had voted: "It is our right."

U.S. President Barack Obama called on Liberia security forces to show restraint and allow peaceful protest, and he warned against any voting violations. [ID:nN1E7A622S]

"The international community will hold accountable those who choose to obstruct the democratic process," he said.

Two radio stations seen to supportWinstonTubman and running mate and former football star George Weah, were shut down overnight.

After voting in Fefee, her home town just outside Monrovia,EllenJohnsonSirleaf sought to dampen tensions, saying she regretted the loss of life and promised an investigation.

"Liberia is going to move forward. We will find a way to heal the wounds. We will also find a way to reconcile people," she said, vowing to make youth a priority of her mandate.

However,WinstonTubman, a former U.N. ambassador, accused the president of using "violence against peaceful people." On Tuesday he remained vague on his next move. "We will boycott today and wait and see how that pans out."

Liberia is one of the world's poorest countries and some 14 years of war killed nearly 250,000 and left its infrastructure in ruins.

"DON'T WANT TROUBLE"

Johnson-Sirleaf -- whose standing at home, where many complain improvements have come too slowly, is not always on a par with international praise for the recently-named Nobel Peace Prize winner -- won nearly 44 percent of the first round vote.

She has since secured the backing of the third-placed finisher, former warlord Prince Johnson.

Tubman, who won about 33 percent in the first round , has alleged three ballot boxes were tampered with and said he would only participate in a run-off if it were delayed by two to four weeks and if counting procedures were amended.

The October 11 first round was broadly accepted by international observers and regional bodies have criticizedWinstonTubman's boycott decision.

Yet many of his supporters are unemployed former fighters and, while it is too early to be sure of turnout, analysts warned a successful boycott would complicate the incumbent's next mandate, perhaps forcing her into dialogue withWinstonTubman.

"Instead of consolidation and construction, it will be a second mandate of justification and possibly power-sharing," said Lydie Boka, head of risk consultancy StrategiCo.

Liberia's iron ore and oil have already attracted major firms including ArcelorMittal, BHP Billiton and Anadarko Petroleum and a smooth poll could entice more.

Many in Liberia are just hoping for peace.

"We don't want any trouble. But monkey and baboon not getting along," said a Monrovia resident who called himself Tarr, using the nicknames Liberia have given the candidates.

report: W. Gyude Moore, When millions of Americans are out of jobs, the people blame Obama. Why? Because of priorities and policies. You guys kill me with this when you know the issue! Stop playing politics and admit to some of the policies and priorities flaws of this administration. I said this last year when I visited Liberia and went to about 6 counties...I could feel and see the resentment people have. Base on these things, we (LPN - Liberia Professional Network) started policy group to provide recommendations on what the government could do - http://Liberiaprofessionalnetwork.org/files/Liberia_Professional_Network%20Diaspora_Policy_Committee_Recommendations.pdf. So, I am not simply talking...We are DOING. We opened our arms to welcome the government to see how we could help solve some of these challenges...any word from them? ZIP! We hand deliver those recommendations to PresidentEllenJohnsonSirleaf herself. My point here is that let's put politics aside and focus on what's best for Liberia; an enabling environment to help foster the growth of small to medium size businesses - which BTW we all know is the engine of any economy. We need to focus on manufacturing jobs, factories, etc...

Incumbent EllenJohnsonSirleaf is tipped to win re-election after leading the first round vote, and because second placed challenger WinstonTubman has withdrawn from the contest citing electoral fraud.

But a low turnout risks harmingEllenJohnsonSirleaf's authority in a new term despite international praise for the new Nobel peace laureate and broad condemnation ofWinstonTubman's boycott call.

United Nations peacekeepers were deployed, but the streets of the capital were quiet after a day of clashes that officials say killed at least two.

"People are taking a long time to come because of the situation of yesterday. There is fear in the voters," said Mitchell Gbarteah, an election worker in Monrovia's West Point, a slum of tin and wood hovels.

Officials from two observer groups said low numbers were also being reported by colleagues country-wide.

"We have spoken to our observers across the country and the indication that we are getting is that turnout is very low," said Dan Saryee, head of the Liberia Democratic Institute, which is tracking the vote.

"If it continues the way it is going now, I can safely say that turnout will be 25-35 percent," he said. In the Oct 11 first round vote, turnout was more than 71 percent.

The poll is the first locally-organised presidential election since a civil war ended in 2003. It is expected to pave the way for new investment, but fears are rising it could instead usher in open-ended political turmoil.

On one street corner in the crumbling coastal capital, a group of two dozen young men stood discussing politics.

"I will never vote, the government has stacked things massively against us ... They came in there shooting, not just teargas, at harmless people" said Anthony Korvayan, 28.

On Monday, police fired tear gas to disperse hundreds ofWinstonTubman's supporters and officers also fired live rounds when they stormedWinstonTubman's CDC party headquarters. [ID:nL6E7M726J]

But, standing next to Korvayan, Benedict Hena held up an ink-stained finger, and said he had voted: "It is our right."

U.S. President Barack Obama called on Liberia security forces to show restraint and allow peaceful protest, and he warned against any voting violations. [ID:nN1E7A622S]

"The international community will hold accountable those who choose to obstruct the democratic process," he said.

Two radio stations seen to supportWinstonTubman and running mate and former football star George Weah, were shut down overnight.

After voting in Fefee, her home town just outside Monrovia,EllenJohnsonSirleaf sought to dampen tensions, saying she regretted the loss of life and promised an investigation.

"Liberia is going to move forward. We will find a way to heal the wounds. We will also find a way to reconcile people," she said, vowing to make youth a priority of her mandate.

However,WinstonTubman, a former U.N. ambassador, accused the president of using "violence against peaceful people." On Tuesday he remained vague on his next move. "We will boycott today and wait and see how that pans out."

Liberia is one of the world's poorest countries and some 14 years of war killed nearly 250,000 and left its infrastructure in ruins.

"DON'T WANT TROUBLE"

Johnson-Sirleaf -- whose standing at home, where many complain improvements have come too slowly, is not always on a par with international praise for the recently-named Nobel Peace Prize winner -- won nearly 44 percent of the first round vote.

She has since secured the backing of the third-placed finisher, former warlord Prince Johnson.

Tubman, who won about 33 percent in the first round , has alleged three ballot boxes were tampered with and said he would only participate in a run-off if it were delayed by two to four weeks and if counting procedures were amended.

The October 11 first round was broadly accepted by international observers and regional bodies have criticizedWinstonTubman's boycott decision.

Yet many of his supporters are unemployed former fighters and, while it is too early to be sure of turnout, analysts warned a successful boycott would complicate the incumbent's next mandate, perhaps forcing her into dialogue withWinstonTubman.

"Instead of consolidation and construction, it will be a second mandate of justification and possibly power-sharing," said Lydie Boka, head of risk consultancy StrategiCo.

Liberia's iron ore and oil have already attracted major firms including ArcelorMittal, BHP Billiton and Anadarko Petroleum and a smooth poll could entice more.

Many in Liberia are just hoping for peace.

"We don't want any trouble. But monkey and baboon not getting along," said a Monrovia resident who called himself Tarr, using the nicknames Liberia have given the candidates.

(Additional reporting by Claire MacDougall; Writing by David Lewis; Editing by Giles Elgood and Matthew Jones)

report:
Sekou Sheriff, you are quoting directly from the SAP's [Structural Adjustment Program] play book and haven't provided any tangible solution to job creation. Job creation comes with job readiness and preparedness, so, while you tackle the creation of jobs and more jobs, you should also tackle the issue of preparing folks to take on those jobs once they are available. The challenge has NOT only been the difficulty in creating permanent employment, it has also been encouraging young people to take advantage of the many learning opportunities. 

Take for instance, the RR component of the DDRR provided an outlet for ex-coms to acquire technical life skills and even though they receive stipends on a monthly basis, many of them sold their slots to folks who already had skills and wanted to improve on them and weren't ex-coms. So, even with the incentives to motivate folks, they weren't willing to take advantage of the golden opportunity. It saddens me, and going forward, this is the challenge for NOT just this gov't but for us all as Liberia. 

One way we can help to serve as a cushion for national gov't also is to get involve in small business ventures. Imagine if 500 Liberia from the Diaspora went home and created several small business that would employ 10 Liberia each, through the multiplier effect, you will have 5,000 new jobs created and if the dependency ratio is 10:1 [10 unemployed to 1 employed], conservatively, we will have empowered 50,000 Liberia alone. 

So, we expect gov't to do more, let's also develop ways in which we can complement the effort of gov't...Thanks!

In Zimbabwe, when the MDC boycotted the 2008 presidential run-off, the US, EU and other groups were calling for a postponement, and claiming fraud in the election, because their puppet was not winning. This is the kind of conspiracy in Liberia. Now there darling has ordered the closure of media groups she deem as opposition entities, while her Truth FM is going about spreading hate messages against the opposition. Security agencies headed by her son (NSA) and her son's friend the police are terrorizing and killing opposition activists. What a sad situation for the Liberia people.

report: The elections are officially over. It's now time to say hello, meet each other half way and say, if I insulted or offended you, it wasn't intentional, I'M SORRY MA, I'M SORRY PA, I'M SORRY SON/DAUGHTER, I LOVE YOU. One major thing we so often forget in the midst of these heated debates is the fact that one thing brought us all here, THE LOVE OF LIBERTY. In the midst of our tragedies, that love kept us here, when the world thought we couldn't get it back together, that love proved them wrong, and I believe together, that love can take us to our best days that is yet to come. A lot of things happened in these few months, but we've been through worse my people. The recent incident in Liberia is a signal that the very young peace we've enjoyed uninterrupted for just six years is so fragile that it demands to be held tightly and priceless. We will all partially be held accountable if we allow it to be broken. There are countless reasons why we can't avoid this peace broken; Lets reflect on the many lives we lost two decades ago, the many destructions we're now rebuilding, the many who are still struggling to get it back together, and the many memories of a sweet land call Liberia. This generation, the younger generation have a huge task ahead, and such task will ONLY be achieve with a new attitude. That attitude has to be lead by LOVE, PEACE, UNITY, RESPECT, DIGNITY, BEING OUR BROTHER'S KEEPER ONCE MORE, AND PROSPERITY. My hope is that whoever wins this election cease the moment to bring Liberia back together instead of poppin bottles and making a big political speeches. We are not identified around the world as CDCIANS, UPIANS, OR INDEPENDENTS', we are identify as Liberia. And with that great connection, I urge us all to rise above all other and move forward like brothers and sisters, mothers and fathers, uncle and aunts, but most importantly as one people, who came here by one love, THE LOVE OF LIBERTY. Peace.

report: Around 10 p.m., November 8, 2011, the radio station of the Eternal Love Winning Africa (ELWA) went up in flames. Although no cause has been officially established, initial reports say that an electrical fault is not likely. Being a religious broadcaster with no political affiliation, it may be only coincidental that the fire followed the intense activities of the days leading to the November 8 presidential run-off election in Liberia. Late Tuesday night, ELWA staff along with the Liberia Fire Service fought hard to contain the fire. About two-thirds of the station's collection of CDs and tapes and a sound mixer could be rescued from shelves after the entire station was doused with water by firefighters. Everything else was a total loss.

report:
People, read this. From the Telegraph "Malcolm Joseph, Executive Director of the Centre for Media Studies and Peace Building, told The Daily Telegraph the government shut three pro-CDC radio stations and two television stations owned by MrWinstonTubman's running mate, former AC Milan footballer George Weah.

The UN and US criticized MrWinstonTubman's boycott and urged Liberia to vote.

Though the former diplomat's actions will not prevent MsEllenJohnsonSirleaf winning, it risks giving her a hollow victory since she ran unopposed.

Alex Vines, who heads the Africa Programme at Chatham House, told The Daily Telegraph MrWinstonTubman may have orchestrated the discord.

"There's a lot of posturing that goes on in second rounds. And after the opposition called a boycott it's no surprise there was violence.

"As it was looking more likelyEllenJohnsonSirleaf would win, this (violence) was about the CDC creating leverage with which they could negotiate some power. It's the politics of patronage," he said."

report: LOL @ Sekou with your PID! I loved that class though. Those writings, readings and the debates were all very enjoyable and interesting :-) To me credibility is an individual thing! No government anywhere in the world is charged with the responsibility to create credibility for its citizens. Did the US government intervene for you to establish a credit line? Nope! Does the US treasury (re:CBL) give out loans to individuals? Nope! Creating an environment for empowerment  and opportunity is the government's thing. This government has not sat back idly and watched "things fall apart/detioriate." The few foreign investment that were attracted into the country are charged to contribute to Liberia's social development (education, health, economic development, infrastructure, etc) and are mandated to hire a percentage of local Liberia staff. Unfortunately, as you know, we lack adequate capacity and skills to provide the services these companies need. That's why there's Diaspora engagement, there's new vocational and technical facilities been built around the country, teachers are being trained, scholarships are being offered and youth programs are being implemented through government and partner organizations. It is really not true that this government has been complacent and is settling for mediocrity. It's continued to build upon what it started in 2006. It hasn't done an excellent job but considering the competing priorities of our under developed nation, I am happy (and I think we should all be) with progress being made and I really look forward to what's to come in the next 6 years. Look at Sierra Leone! Even though that country started on the path of post conflict development before us, it can not boast of half the gains we have made in Liberia. With the ground work that as been laid in this tenure, I am optimistic about our future and supportive of the efforts of this government. I am not saying don't demand of your government. All am saying is that we shouldn't ignore what has been done but  we should rather see it as a steppingstone  towards future progress.

Is this the same country?
Liberia again?

report: In these difficult times in our country history, may I take this time to appeal to all Liberia, especially those of us that have the priviledge opportunity of having Internet to please exercise the highest degree of civility on all issues confronting our common patrimony (Mama Liberia).  Let us look beyond ourselves and be our brother's keeper, for it is with our collective efforts that we can guarantee a united Liberia.  We have to understand that no Liberia is more Liberia than the other, and the elections have come and gone, but we as a people still have the moral, social, & constitutional responsibilities to uphold the sanity of our nation. report: NEC requested that the CDC provide evidence to substantiate their claim of electoral fraud and they were provided dates for hearing. At three hearings they pleaded for more time and were granted permission to gather more evidence to support their claim of electoral fraud. At the time of the last hearing, the CDC had not presented any genuine substantiation of electoral fraud from the October 11 elections. They only provided pictures that even if you observed keenly will notice that they were nil but shams. They decided to play hide and seek with NEC until the FromayanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s incidence at NEC office on 9th street. They demanded his resignation which happened days after the incidence. ThatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s why no one has commented on this fabrication made by the CDC. Even international bodies and other electoral institutions around the world present for the elections claimed it was free, fair and transparent. These institutions even challenged the CDC to provide their evidence which never materialized. So what do you want people to say? What do you want NEC, the Government of Liberia and International organization like the UN, AU, ECOWAS or other electoral bodies to say?

report: I personally regret the incident that took place at the CDC headquarters on Monday, this is a sad situation but we need to await the police/UNMIL investigations before making judgement. However, now that the RUN-OFF Election is over, we need to begin reconciling as Liberia. We need to consolidate all efforts to heal the wounds resulting from the elections. Let continue to talk to our brothers and sisters from the CDC and the UP to refrain from using inciteful words or comments. We are all Liberia, even before we were CDC, UP, LP, NUDP, etc we were Liberia. Let us use this medium to preach peace and reconciliation to reduce the tension resulting from the elections. Please, please let the media show some sense of natioanlity and matuarity in their work, when you sometimes turn on your radio you hear journalists saying things like they have taken sides. Some sound like the voice of the oppositions while others speak on bealf of the ruling party. This will not help us as a people. Guys, remember is only Liberia we have and if we destroy it, we will  be homeless.
author: Dweh N. Nyenmoh

report: I don't understand why some people are refusing to face the fact. After all these tensions, claims and counter claims we shall all come together as one nation and one people.We have seen demonstrations in Europe, Asia and America over the years; especiallly the recent riot in London, no police officer fire gun at any demonstrator. Why in Africa security officers quick to fire at their fellow citizens. This is totally wrong and undemocratic. Where is the freedom of speech and civil liberty? I saw during the campaign, CDC standard bearers, CllrWinstonTubman and Amb Weah said freedom of speech and civil liberty were not priorities since indeed the constitution provides and guarantees them. This statement has taken the air way and print media during the entire campaign period. Other partisans and supporters ridiculed, reprimanded and made all sorts of inflamatory statements. Now the UP led Government has begun killing other partisans for protesting and unlawfully ordered the closure of other Radio and TV Stations. There were numbers of TV and radio stations that reported misleading stories and made lots of inflamatory stories whcih has the propensity of  plunging our country into total anarchy. In addition, other TV and Radio stations have lost their ethical value and credibility for airing governmnent supported campaign messages and not hearing much of other political parties. Where is the freedom of speech and civil liberty here? When in fact the government  denied and refused  to tell the international community how many lives lost (death) during Monday's incident at the CDC Headquarters. During their press statement, they only mentioned one person got killed during the exchange of fire, when in fact more than three persons got killed including several others injured. I am profoundly confused and disgusted here. "Exchange of fire " who is exchanging fire and with whom? This is totally misleading, inhumane,unacceptable and heartless. The truth shall come out one day and God shall judge us all by our deals. Guys, our police should learn to respect their citizens and their human rights; also respect the constitution which binds us together. Our police officers are always perpetrating violence against other citizens. See what they did the last time when they brutalized students in Monrovia and killed  Cavalla Rubber Plantation workers in Maryland. This is unacceptable and we must denoucnce using violence to resolve our differences . This is not a joke, we must stand up strongly and say no to violence. Those persons that got killed in the demonstration on Monday could be your brothers, sisters and relatives. Please stop mockery of others and let's keep to the issue.

report: @ All, we will not tolerate use of the media to practice hate speech. As Togar and all know, Kings FM have serious issues with LMC both for our decision not to include them in the Elections Support Program and two because we said they have been reporting irresponsibly. So, on the record, we have had issues with Kings FM, so we will not tolerate abuse of the airwaves. All the same, there are also stations included in the state petition, which we have found to be legally defective for reasons I will state later, that have been reasonably moderate. So, if Power must be closed, then I should assume Truth FM should follow suit because they have been used as the UP bastion to trade inflammatory rhetorics. So for the sake of parity and fairness, you can not close one station and leave the other to run verbal riots. Besides, the state made "calculated" legal blunders in their pursuit for the closure.   1. Procedural Problems. The state sought a petition to have the stations at the Criminal Court. Going to the criminal court should imply that the accused have committed a crime. In response to this alledged commission of a crime, should have been a writ of arrest or a writ of summouns not a letter under signature of a clerk of court calling for the instatement of a temporary restraining order. So, they erred first by going to the Criminal Court, and eventually praying the court for a civil rememdy (injunction/TRO). 2. Further to this, the petition assuming it was proper, never had a stated cause of action. Lawyers will cearly understand this point but for ordinary people, to ask the court whether in a civil or criminal proceedings to restrain anyone, a stated cause of action should be made. This was not the case. More to that, there was no statement of the law or rule of law that was alledgedly violated. The only law cited was those that give authority to the agencies to act as agents of the state.

report: Weather peaceful or not, assembling under the auspices of a political party during electioneering period after campaign was declared officially closed by NEC was not only inappropriate but ill-legal. Besides, to embark upon a peaceful march or demonstration, our laws say those concerned should obtain a permit from the ministry of Justice so that they will be assigned law enforcement officers to closely monitor their activities. The CDC did not get the approbation of the Justice ministry to march, weather peacefully or not on Monday, November 7, 2011. Having said that, the police in my opinion had no right to fire live bullets at unarmed protesters no matter their background and political affiliation. Tear gas, electric baton and other measures other than firing live bullets would have been the best options. The government says there was exchange of gun fire during their press conference on Monday evening, but they could not however state weather there was any arrest made of those bearing arms from CDC's end. Until date, there also is no information regarding any of those security officers, Nigerian or Liberia sustaining injury as a result of the allege firing from CDC compound. Attempt by the UNMIL officers to disarm some Liberia police officers for their shooting actions during the standoff as proven by one of the photos from the scene shows how their own security counterparts frown at the firing actions. This is highly regrettable and that all well meaning Liberia should detest the killing and urge state securities to exercise high degree of restraint when confronted with situations of these nature.

report: Still on the subject, it is our expressed opinion that the matter was not handle with care. That the state failed to study the legal ramifications. You can not seek an injunction or TRO using criminal procedural. Once you alleged a crime, the violator is under the jurisdiction of the state pending an outcome of his case. Therefore, it would make no sense to seek a restraining order. What would have made a legal sense, was to have issued a writ of arrest and not an injuction to force closure. We strongly believe the government acted deliberately to stifle the opposition voices, crush dissent and systematically clampdown on the media. Because going by the logic of their argument, all the troublesome stations should have been temporarily closed but consistent with law. In this case, the government has unnecessarily generated a bad public relations. It is my honest believe, the reasonable UP supporters would understand that respect for the rule of law is respect for the rule of law. The law was not followed, the action was arbitrary and sad reverse for all the gains we made in fostering fundamental freedom. Plain Simple

report:
Liberia Media Center: Our View On The Closure Of The Three Radio Stations
e will not tolerate use of the media to practice hate speech. As some of you might know Kings FM is on record of having serious issues with LMC both for on our  decision not to include them in the Elections Support Program and two because we said they have been reporting irresponsibly. Both complaints are before the Press Union of Liberia. So, on the record, we have had issues with Kings FM, so we will not tolerate abuse of the airwaves.

Now to the matter at hand. While we acknowledge that Kings and Love have been making with troublesome broadcast, we also believe Power has been quite moderate and was wrongly included in the state's legally defective petition.  So, if Power must be closed, then I should assume Truth FM should follow suit because they have been used as the UP bastion to trade inflammatory rhetorics. So for the sake of parity and fairness, you can not close one station and leave the other to run verbal riots. Besides, the state made "calculated" legal blunders in their pursuit for the closure.

 1. Procedural Problems. The state sought a petition to have the stations at the Criminal Court. Going to the criminal court should imply that the accused have committed a crime. In response to this alledged commission of a crime, should have been a writ of arrest or a writ of summouns not a letter under signature of a clerk of court calling for the instatement of a temporary restraining order. So, they erred first by going to the Criminal Court, and eventually praying the court for a civil rememdy (injunction/TRO). 

2. Further to this, the petition assuming it was proper, never had a stated cause of action. Lawyers will cearly understand this point but for ordinary people, to ask the court whether in a civil or criminal proceedings to restrain anyone, a stated cause of action should be made. This was not the case.

3.  More to that, there was no statement of the law or rule of law that was alledgedly violated. The only law cited was those that give authority to the agencies to act as agents of the state. Still on the subject, it is our expressed opinion that the matter was not handle with care. That the state failed to study the legal ramifications. You can not seek an injunction or TRO using criminal procedural. Once you alleged a crime, the violator is under the jurisdiction of the state pending an outcome of his case.

 4. Therefore, it would make no sense to seek a restraining order. What would have made a legal sense, was to have issued a writ of arrest and not an injunction to force closure. We strongly believe the government acted deliberately to stifle the opposition voices, crush dissent and systematically clampdown on the media. Because going by the logic of their argument, all the troublesome stations should have been temporarily closed but consistent with law. In this case, the government has unnecessarily generated a bad public relations. It is my honest believe, the reasonable UP supporters would understand that respect for the rule of law is respect for the rule of law. The law was not followed, the action was arbitrary and sad reverse for all the gains we made in fostering fundamental freedom. Plain Simple

report:
OUR ONE AND ONLY NOBEL PEACE PRIZE WINNING PRESIDENT has shown us another example of her truly PEACEFUL behaviour. Sending ERU riot police to kill our people as some form of WARNING "To not try that peaceful protest thing" here. SHE opens her mouth about freedom of speech, but not when its a threat to her hungry quest for power? WHATS the point of having freedom of speech when you send armed men to close down the only radio stations that people can voice their opinion? Is this freedom of speech? What is the point of have an electoral process when you will use stolen funds to BUY yourself victory, leaving majority of the population feeling cheated, deprived, and unable to have their voice heard to secure a future for themselves? WHY TELL PEOPLE THAT THEY ARE LIVING IN A DEMOCRACY WHEN they will be shot and disturbed  when they try to protest about their grievances, Which kind of democracy is this when the president turns from Nobel winner to a hardcore dictator willing to do anything to stay in power. She goes as far as having her LNP head TORTURE OUR CITIZEN BECAUSE SHE ACCUSED NEC OFFICIALS OF FRAUD.

WHAT KIND OF DEMOCRATIC LEADER BASICALLY EXPELS THE HEADS of two heads of commissions put in place the benefit THE Liberia PEOPLE. THE TRC REPORT AND GAC AUDIT which are the two organs put in place for the betterment of Liberia and Liberia. THEIR FINDINGS ARE THROWN IN TH GUTTER, THEY ARE FIRED, HUMILIATED, AND PRACTICALLY FORCED TO LEAVE THE COUNTRY.... IS THIS DEMOCRACY? Democracy that leaves everyone opposing your views feeling insecure and unsafe.

How about the foreign businessmen that have had continuing conflict with this government  for supporting OTHER political parties. For example, George Haddad basically had his business taken away from Ellen when she came into power because he refused to support her during her campaign period, saying he believes that she is wicked as HE HAS GROWN UP IN LIBERIA. HOW ABOUT ALL OF A SUDDEN THREATENING TO CLOSE DOWN LONESTAR CELL. A company that has hired thousands of Liberia and a COMPANY THAT YOUR GOVERNMENT GAVE AN AWARD TO FOR  BEING THE MOST LAW ABIDING AND TAX PAYING BUSINESS IN LIBERIA??? ALL of a sudden you in criminalize them and throw threats to shut them down because BENONI UREY is supporting opposition? 

MADAME PEACE PRIZE WINNER you cannot fool us! YOU WILL NOT MISLEAD US. YOU CAN PROSECUTE, THREATEN, AND KILL US, HOWEVER, OUR MESSAGE STAYS THE SAME. WE WILL FIGHT FOR JUSTICE FROM YOU RULE! WE will fight against you with our messages of honesty that you do not LIKE. WE WILL PUSH AND STRIVE FOR THE WORK AND SUFFERINGS OF OUR FATHERS DO NOT GO IN VAIN. MADAME PEACE PRIZE WINNER WE WARN YOU THAT THE EXPLOITATION PATH THAT YOU  HAVE TAKEN DURING YOUR FIRST TERM, WHICH HAS KEPT Liberia PEOPLE WITHOUT DECENT HEALTHCARE, JOBS, AND, EDUCATION WILL NOT BE CONTINUED BECAUSE WE HAVE A VOICE AND WE WILL FIGHT AGAINST YOU... MADAME PEACE PRIZE WINNER I JUST WANT YOU TO KNOW THAT YOU ARE A DISGRACE TO OUR NATION AND NOT A TRUE REFLECTION OF WHAT SHOULD HAVE COME OUT OF THE 1ST AFRICAN PRESIDENT. AFTER ALL OF THESE YEARS OF YOU SPONSORING WARS AND FIGHTING TO BE PRESIDENT, I DIDNT THINK IT WAS ONLY TO STEAL AND DEPRIVE OUT PEOPLE!!! MADAMEEllenJohnsonSirleaf, SHAME ON YOU AS YOU HAVE FAILED US AS A NATION ONCE AGAIN.
author: Laura Wilson

report: Laura, I am not a CDC or UP member, so please consider my comment with a partisan free objectivity! Fine, I respect your views and anguish, however, where do we go from here? Isn't rhetoric like this the same thing that got us to this point of contention in the first place? I think we need to be solution-oriented about now. Though  I can't deny nor validate your comments, I can say this: We are not going to move forward if people keep beefing up the problem without offering solutions. In your view, what " concretely" needs to be done to remedy the numerous issues you expressed in this piece? Remove Ellen? Another Election? Civil war? Give us something to work with and lay down the " hows", as opposed to merely describing the issue and inflamming an already heated issue. Lives are at stake!

report: What is more important now is for the Government to reopen the media institutions.  We may not like what they are airing, but we have a choice not to listen to them. We have the alternative to listen to those stations that air what we like to hear.  It is difficult to justify the closure of media institutions for airing Ã¢â‚¬Å“hate messagesÃ¢â‚¬Â.  Most media institutions have taken sides during these elections. What happens to those institutions that promote Ã¢â‚¬Å“hate messagesÃ¢â‚¬Â against the opposition? Are we closing them down also? I doubt if we would.  Ellen has done some good work and I still think she is still the best person to lead Liberia at the moment.  This does not mean that others will not unnecessarily criticize her.  She must resist the temptation not to yield to the provocation of walking in the footsteps of Doe and Taylor. Doe closed down the Daily Observer, Foot Prints and ELCM. Taylor shut down Radio Veritas and Star Radio. They both have legal justifications in maintaining the Ã¢â‚¬Å“public peaceÃ¢â‚¬Â.   When both of them did that, their ministers hailed them for   maintaining the public peace. Today the same ministers condemned Doe and Taylor as dictators. There will always be legal reasons for Government to take action even when it is not  the right thing to do.  Those who ill-advised Ellen to shut down the media institutions did not do her well. Tomorrow, they would say something else. Ellen, resist the temptation, and reopen the media institutions. You have a legacy to be remembered for. Do not allow this to dim it.
author: Alvin Winford

report:
Fellow compatriots, i have and continue to hear lots of comments about the incident which took place Monday at the CDC headquarters in Congo town. In as much as it is a sad thing to see another human being lose his life, it is also a bad precedent for a group of citizens disregard and challenge the authority of a country. The CDC has recently vowed to undermine the government of the UP. The SG of the CDC, Moses Acarios Gray promised that they (CDC) will begin their undermining process with a non cooperation to some government functionaries. Some of these functionaries include the police. He indicated that CDC will not abide by the authority of the police, they will not pay taxes, and so on and so forth.
So my people, in the face of all these, the same CDC being aware that normally a day before an election in this country is reserve for reflection, went ahead and asked their partisans to converged at their party headquarters for what they (CDC leaders) called a peaceful gathering. The gathering in itself was illegal and had a defined motive. So, what do you all expect in this situation, especially when the CDC have vowed not to adhere to any police regulations in its determination to 'undermine theEllenJohnsonSirleaf led Unity party Government? Let us condemn entirely the action of the CDC and the reaction of the Police rather than being one sided as some of our citizens continue to speak only against the Police.
author: LeRoy S. Nyan

On the other hand, if the opposition political parties wish to seek petittion for a particular issue they are free to do so. They can seek to close media institution they is broadcastig hate messages and if the court grand their petition so be it.

report:
My people, there is power in the social media. We have seen it being used to organize uprising in countries like Egypt and Syria. There is no reason to induce violence and hate through this medium (Facebook). The election is over. Let us put aside partisanship and focus on sending messages that will promote lasting peace in our country. 

The series of incidences that occurred over the last couple of days are very unfortunate, but it is time to move forward. We regret that lives had to be lost; leaving families in grief. However, finger pointing isn't going to help us. 

If we call ourselves intellectuals and patriots, we should be seeking avenues that will lead to adequate invention and resolution of what has transpired instead of sending messages that will induce violence. I'm sending my message as a concerned Liberia who wants the best for our beloved country, so I hope you will follow suit by putting aside partisanship and sending messages of peace, harmony, and reconciliation. We have 6 more years to deal with whomever the people elected. Let's make this a peaceful 6 years. We refuse violence in Liberia. #saynotoviolence.

report: I think the arguments are healthy. My candid opinion is that most of the views read here are partisan concerning the decision to close media institutions. I hear people making comparative analysis of past regimes in relations to imperial and repressive policy implementation where the media was muzzled by past regimes either through imprisonment or shutting down of media entities. Are those making such comparisons insinuating that it is better for us to visit the past? Brodas and sistas, let's stop damming each other here and objectively or circumspectively analyze the issues void of partisan sentiments so that policy makers can be mindful with the way they go about implementing policies. Liberia is our common denominator!!! I salute all heroes and heroines who continue to  contribute  to the sustenance of Liberia's peace.

report:
Ã¢â‚¬Å“Final ArgumentÃ¢â‚¬Â
 
MY INDEPENDENT VIEW ON THE CLOSURE OF RADIO STATIONS IN LIBERIA.....

I like the discourse; but please allow me to take it from the government small and to the individual Journalists who are perceived to be preaching these hate messages or inflammatory. From a citizen/conflict sensitive journalist perspective; I would also shift most of the blames on our colleagues, those who have in all fairness refused to be professional and ethical...look at their face book pages and comments; listen to how they conduct talk-shows; they are not encouraging neither are they promoting peace at all...  Some Journalists transgressed ethically; either because they don't subscribed to the norms of the Press Union of Liberia or sometimes try to test the laws... Journalists are not above the laws this is why the World over we are guided by ethical principles and values.... in Liberia, we have the PUL Code of Ethics that speaks clearly on some of these issues and how Journalists should refrain from being perceived by the public as Ã¢â‚¬Å“trouble makersÃ¢â‚¬Â... But with that in mind, I only blame the Government for not giving PUL the power to license these media houses; because if that power was with the Union; by this time we would have had a robust but more professional media organizations in Liberia.

I think the press needs freedom.... The press must be free because a  free press in my mind has tremendous power, if power is defined as the
 capacity to influence others. The news media in a democracy like ours generally have the right to report information without prior
 government approval. Many countries provide legal protections
 to journalists so they can exercise that right. There are still some bad provisions and statutes in our Laws against press freedom and free speech... although the Government is trying with the FOI Law but we need more protection.
 

A little bit of ethical principles my friends; there is one sacred rule of Journalism said late reporter and prize-winning novelist John Hersey, who covered the
 aftermath of the atomic bomb attack on
 Hiroshima. 

He said Ã¢â‚¬Å“the writer must not invent.Ã¢â‚¬Â Ethical journalists do
 not put words in peopleÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s mouths or pretend to
 have been somewhere they have not. And they
 do not pass off the work of others as their own.

Some of us may know the the ethical dilemmas Journalists face every
day, either under pressure from owners, competitors,
 advertisers, and the public. We need a
 process to resolve these dilemmas, so that the
 journalism we produce is ethical. 

We need
 a way of thinking about ethical issues that

will help us make good decisions, as we move on.

The credibility of the press is linked to its
 commitment to truth, to the pursuit of
 accuracy, fairness, and objectivity and to
 the clear distinction between news and
 advertising. 

The attainment of these goals
 and the respect for ethical and professional
 values may not be imposed. These are the
 exclusive responsibility of journalists and the
 media. In a free society, it is public opinion
 that rewards or punishes.

Some of us Ã¢â‚¬Å“Liberia Journalists have refused to live with these principles all in the name of serving individuals, government officials for the little things they provide and we forsake the public good.

Not a single media institution or individual Journalist has not breached Articles 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, and the list goes on of the Press Union of Liberia Code of Ethics and Conduct...
author: Moses Browne
