 do not pass off the work of others as their own.

Some of us may know the the ethical dilemmas Journalists face every
day, either under pressure from owners, competitors,
 advertisers, and the public. We need a
 process to resolve these dilemmas, so that the
 journalism we produce is ethical. 

We need
 a way of thinking about ethical issues that

will help us make good decisions, as we move on.

The credibility of the press is linked to its
 commitment to truth, to the pursuit of
 accuracy, fairness, and objectivity and to
 the clear distinction between news and
 advertising. 

The attainment of these goals
 and the respect for ethical and professional
 values may not be imposed. These are the
 exclusive responsibility of journalists and the
 media. In a free society, it is public opinion
 that rewards or punishes.

Some of us Ã¢â‚¬Å“Liberia Journalists have refused to live with these principles all in the name of serving individuals, government officials for the little things they provide and we forsake the public good.

Not a single media institution or individual Journalist has not breached Articles 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, and the list goes on of the Press Union of Liberia Code of Ethics and Conduct...

Dirty Politics!!! 

I Ponder, is this how our country, democracy and peace will be threaten after every 6years??
Why our politicians are never afraid to divide the people of the country and drag our peace into the gutters when its elections time?  When will politicians get to understand that elections are not meant to divide the country??
When will Liberia begin to respect the Law of this country?  I asked all these questions because we Liberia fail to realize that dirty politics is the root cause to this problem today.
When one party comes out and say another party consist of hooligans, illiterate thugs who have a plan or a Document to drag or plunge this country into chaos
The other party on the other hand refuses to remain Civil and accept political defeat but rather involve into making statements that threaten the peace and security of the country and the people they seek to govern and remain disobedient to the rule of law and a sitting Government.
All of these put the state security forces on a very high alert or against a certain group of people.  The state security acted in the manner in which it did because of the Dirty Politics that ensue the political process in our country. Citizens who are neither UP nor CDC partisan lost their properties and some were even hospitalize all because of this Dirty Politics. 
If we Liberia want to be truly reconciled, we must do away with Dirty politics in this country.

report: There are two types of electorial  violence, it is in a study of these that solutions are found. The first is were a state has deep- rooted pwer asymmetries. In such cases, there will be no structural change with out reveloutionary transformation. I would suggest that there be focus on fundamental institutional reform across all specturms  of the national election commission of Liberia. The second is were election violence occurs when the election commission mismange  election information like one that took place in recent time in Liberia or rigging, theft, and irregularity and manipulation. In these cases electorial reform whichcorrect these flaws canlead to sound electoral  system that prevent the recurrence of future electorial violence. Most African countries fall in the first category.

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)
author: Lawrence Randall

report:
Liberia challenger warns of turmoil unless poll delayed
Mon Nov 7, 2011 9:51am GMT


WinstonTubman of Liberia's opposition Congress for Democratic Change party arrives at an election rally in Monrovia, November 5, 2011. REUTERS/Finbarr O'Reilly

By Richard Valdmanis and Alphonso Toweh

MONROVIA (Reuters) - Liberia could tip into chaos not seen since its civil war if a presidential run-off election set for Tuesday is not delayed and reorganized, presidential hopeful WinstonTubman said on Sunday.

Tubman, a former United Nations diplomat, was meant to stand against incumbent EllenJohnsonSirleaf in the November 8 run-off but last week withdrew his participation in the process and called for a boycott, citing electoral fraud during the first round of voting last month.

"I think that at the end of the day we will have to evaluate what is likely to be better for the country: delaying the elections or going forward with them in a way that doesn't carry the support of such a big party in the country,"WinstonTubman told Reuters in an interview in the garden of his residence in the capital Monrovia.

"The impact on the region would be huge if we were to descend into chaos again. The whole cycle would begin again, confusion in neighboring countries, people running away, tension in the country. This would be far more costly in the long term than if we were to delay the election for a month."

International election observers called the October 11 poll mostly free and fair, and the United States, regional bloc ECOWAS and the African Union have all criticizedWinstonTubman's decision to boycott the second round.

Tubman's CDC party has accused Liberia's election commission of "massive fraud" during the first-round vote, in whichWinstonTubman took just under 33 percent of the votes toEllenJohnsonSirleaf's nearly 44 percent.

The party said it had evidence that at least three ballot boxes were opened improperly by electoral staff shortly after the vote, and said there were several other inconsistencies that pointed to systematic rigging.

"Calling it massive fraud may be an exaggerated way of talking, but we feel that what happened did not properly reflect the protection of our interests, and we would like to see those interests respected,"WinstonTubman said.

He said he was asking that his party be granted additional access to the vote counting process "so that we can see what is happening" and that a run-off be delayed by between two and four weeks to allow time for campaigning.

The election is the West African state's first locally-organized presidential contest since the end of its civil war in 2003, and was meant to be a gauge of the country's progress and to open the door to mine and oil investment.

A demonstration called by the CDC over the weekend failed to attract large-scale support, but the boycott call has raised fears that some of the party's supporters could try to disrupt voting on Tuesday.

The National Election Commission, whose chairman resigned last week under pressure from the CDC, said the vote would go ahead as planned.

Tubman is pushing for a delay and says he has sought but failed to talk directly toEllenJohnsonSirleaf about the issue.

A spokesman forEllenJohnsonSirleaf deniedWinstonTubman had requested a meeting and added "once he agrees to meet with the president, she will surely welcome him".

NOT MY CHOICE

Johnson-Sirleaf became Africa's first freely elected female head of state in 2005, and has been internationally praised for reducing debt and maintaining peace in a country devastated by 14-years of fighting that killed up to a quarter of a million people.

But she faces criticism within the country for the slow pace of recovery from the war, with more than half the population still living on less than 50 cents a day and most citizens lacking access to power and water.

Tubman, whose running mate in the election is former soccer star George Weah, said that he felt unable to give in to the broad international pressure to reverse his boycott because it risked radicalizing his mostly young, unemployed supporters.

"I cannot on my own say I am pulling my party into this election on the 8th. If I were to do that before convincing my party that this is the way to go, the result would be worse for the process because my party would no longer be influenced by me and I don't know what influences it would fall under."

"It could become more extreme, it could become belligerent," he said.

Tubman said he was urging his supporters not to resort to violence, but he reaffirmed his refusal to recognise results coming from the election and warned of long-term turmoil.

"We will do everything to be calm, law abiding. But there would be problems, I have to admit. People...who want to invest here would think, well, we better take our money elsewhere because Liberia might explode." he said.
author: Yarzeawu Zaza

report: I guess there is no issue here to be discussed. However, since we have reached this stage, it now become compelling to interject our comments. First and foremost, the government, under our law, can sue and be sued. The decision is with court to grant an individual petition on merit. Why people continue to make noise about closing down media institutions that ethically trangressed with the sole intend of endangering the lives of 3.5 million people? Don't you know that it was because of a simple media hate message the resulted to the lost of lives in Rwanda? It was necessary for the government to seek remedy through the court to save lives. Infact those media institutions that broadcast hate messages that led to the Monday violence must be prosecuted along with their godfathers and godmothers. The government would have been on the wrong side only if the police was ordered directly by it to close those stations. It's now time for us to be professional.

The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report:
STOP THE BLAME GAME!!!

It is preposterous for the cynics and pundits to blame PresidentEllenJohnsonSirleaf for the unfortunate incident on November 7th. .  Moreover, it is also ludicrous to accuse the GOL of censoring the press without analyzing the situation. It is a tragedy for any human being to lose his/her live; equally, it behooves the silent majority on here to know that such situation could have been avoided, had those ROGUE POLITICIANS respected the rule of law.

Democracy comes with a responsibility. The rule of law is one of the important elements of democracy; therefore, in order for such practice to be effective, all parties or stakeholders involved should behave responsibly by respecting the laws. Ironically, democratic principles in Africa are usually undermined by (ROGUE POLITICIANS) and some irresponsible journalists whenever there is an election. 

Having emerged from a bloody uncivil war, it is imperative that politicians steer away from inflammatory acts that have the propensity of igniting another unnecessary violence.  On the other hand, journalists should practice responsible journalism. When you have an irresponsible media reporting erroneous and misleading info that might ignite violence, it is incumbent upon the authority to take necessary actions to mitigate such menace. 

Thank God our brave peace officers were able to respond expeditiously to an incendiary act of violence and hooliganism. Liberia will never ever be subjected to lawlessness and mayhem again!!! Anyone who tries to disrupt the peace and tranquility of Liberia will face the full weight of the law!!! God bless Liberia.

Hassan Fadiga
author: Hassan Fadiga

report:
Cyrus W Badio wrote:
REPUBLIC OF LIBERIA
EXECUTIVE MANSION
MONROVIA, LIBERIA
________________________________________

Office of the Press Secretary to the President

PRESS RELEASE

(MONROVIA, LIBERIA - November 8, 2011): President EllenJohnsonSirleaf has expressed deep sorrow and regret over the violence which resulted in the death, Monday, at the headquarters of the opposition, Congress for Democratic Change (CDC). The President said an investigation is currently being conducted, promising that perpetrators will be brought to justice.

An Executive Mansion release says the Liberia leader was speaking to reporters, Tuesday, in Fefeh town, Bomi County, where she had travelled to cast her vote in Presidential run-off election taking place throughout the country.

The President noted that she was pleased with the peaceful conduct of the process and said she was hopeful that, following the election, the country will move forward. The President said she believes that Liberia will find a way to move forward, heal the wounds and reconcile their difference. 

"I think Liberia want peace, they want their basic needs met, and that will be our obligation and our commitment," the President emphasized.

Commenting on the mood of the country in the months leading to 
Inauguration, the President said Liberia will continue to go about their business in a peaceful atmosphere, and predicted a bright future for the country.

Signed: _________________________

 Cyrus Wleh Badio

Press Secretary to the President

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

What I learned from a friend at the AB Robert Funeral Home is, the fellow who was killed during the incident on Monday was a muslin and his family and friends went to get the body for burial according to their Islamic tradition. Upon hearing the news, the police move in and stop the family from moving the body claiming that the body cannot be bury until police investigation and autopsy is carry out.

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report: From the LMC results published so far, 212,128 votes have been tabulated. 1,288,716 people voted on October 11. Taking the difference of these figures give 1,076,588 yet to be tabulate, provided all those that voted last time voted in the runoff, a situation which is unlikely. This represents about 16.46% of the vote cast in the first round!

The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report:
MISSION ACCOMPLISHED

My fellow compatriots, we may have different religions, different tribes, different political ideologies, but we all belong the same country, Liberia. We are Liberia first above everything else. As we close this election season, I would love to extend my hands in peace and unity. Even though the journey may have been rocky, with a lot of political bruises still visible, we just cannot allow this to prevent us from achieving our common goal; the success of mama Liberia. 

This is the time for us to have one end in view, the welfare of Liberia; and let us put aside our differences irrespective of political, tribal, and ideological background to endorse hope over fear. Hence, I am officially disengaging from discussing campaign politics.  It is time to move on, and build us a great nation. IN UNION STRONG, SUCCESS IS SURE. GOD BLESS LIBERIA.
author: Al Hussein Fadiga

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report:
Weah Arrested; Trial Set for January

Three weeks ago, FrontPageAfrica received some information that Mr. George Weah, Vice Standard Bearer of the Congress for Democratic Change was arrested in May this year in the U.S. state of Georgia suburban area, Douglas County, and charged with driving while license suspended or revoked(Miscl) and failure to stop at a stop sign.

Weah was booked and an informer provided FrontPageAfrica with the arrest Mug Shot detailing Mr. WeahÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s inmate number as A69806; Race Black, Sex Male, Age of booking at 44, address 1313 NW 139 Terrace Pembrrook Pine, Fl. 33028. The arrest date is listed as 05/09/2011 at 1:47am.

The county SheriffÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s office informed FrontPageAfrica when contacted recently that the case against Mr. Weah had been transferred to the Douglas County State Court. Ã¢â‚¬Å“He is not in our jail anymore,Ã¢â‚¬Â a representative at the court told FrontPageAfrica.  The official declined to state how long Mr. Weah spent in the county jail but only added that the matter was forwarded to the county court for trial.

Jannissa Miller, a Clerk at the county court when contacted Wednesday, confirmed WeahÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s case number and added that Mr. Weah is due to appear in court next year. Asked for specifics, Miller said: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Right now it is listed for January but that could change depending on lawyers or the judge.Ã¢â‚¬Â

FrontPageAfrica was not able to confirm how long Mr. Weah spent in the county jail and when he was bailed out or who bailed him out of jail. But legal experts say, penalties for Driving on a Suspended License ranges from jail time to fines.
author: Patrick Tarr

report: My special thanks to the many Liberia who risked their security to participate in deciding their future in the runoff election. I like to join US President Barack Obama in calling on Security forces in Liberia to exercise maximum restraint and to allow peaceful protest.  I also like to call on the United Nations mission in Liberia and the Liberia Government to constitute an independent investigation of the CDC March 7 protest exploring the legality of the protest and excessive use of force by the security forces which led to the death of three persons.  I implore the CDC to refrain from accepting its legislative seats won in the just ended election as it will be hypocritical and a disservice to its supporters and the Liberia nation to cite improprieties in the electoral process, stage a tragic protest, abort the runoff, and form part of government brought to power by claims of flaw. To the GOL, I appeal for a speedy and impartial judicial hearing into the issues which led to the closure of three media houses.  To PresidentEllenJohnsonSirleaf, please note that you are about to preside over a deeply divided country as evident by events surrounding this election. It is imperative that the government endeavor to undertake a reconciliation program to unite the nation. Perhaps, it is time we re-review the recommendations of the TRC.  I like to end by calling on the young people, the future of our nation, not to allow their judgment to be clouded by political loyalty, their persons to be used for destabilization, but as vehicles of change. This we must do by objectively tackling the issues that are affecting our nation. It is no crime to disagree with a president you support, a party you are loyal to, or a person you admire.  The NEW Liberia must be built on honesty, objectivity, and above all patriotism. NO ONE OR GROUP IS GREATER THAN LIBERIA. FOR TOO LONG WE HAVE GIVEN OUR ALLEGIANCES TO PERSONALITIES AND ORGANIZATIONS. IT IS TIME WE SHIFT OUR ALLEGIANCE TO THE FLAG AND THE Liberia NATION.
author: Garmondeh Clinton

report: It's unfortunate that after more than 24 hours of the election in Liberia, I'm still reading the postings of negativities, the blame game war, and wounds filled with hatred towards each other. What are the significance of uploading these extremely inflammatory photos? Oh, to show the world what accurred two days ago?? WOW,,, Then why don't we contact CNN instead of just FB? If we really desire the...... world to promulgate the dead body or hurts of one of us, who families are probably mourning right now in Liberia with their head up high for justies, then CNN would be the best publisher. But will that be enough to bring them justice? Haven't the world seen a lot of this mess in Liberia already? Isn't it time to clean up and look to the future together? I guess that will depend on who is being ask, but I think so, if you ask me. Come on my people, we need to stop this mess and get back to work, we've got lots of work to do. If we Liberia are not very caution in our approaches to seek justice or getting Liberia to the levels we want it, this President will come for another six years and go, and we'll still be here discussing/talking about those same problems six years later. I can only hope not.

report:
Weah Arrested; Trial Set for January

Three weeks ago, FrontPageAfrica received some information that Mr. George Weah, Vice Standard Bearer of the Congress for Democratic Change was arrested in May this year in the U.S. state of Georgia suburban area, Douglas County, and charged with driving while license suspended or revoked(Miscl) and failure to stop at a stop sign.

Weah was booked and an informer provided FrontPageAfrica with the arrest Mug Shot detailing Mr. WeahÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s inmate number as A69806; Race Black, Sex Male, Age of booking at 44, address 1313 NW 139 Terrace Pembrrook Pine, Fl. 33028. The arrest date is listed as 05/09/2011 at 1:47am.

The county SheriffÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s office informed FrontPageAfrica when contacted recently that the case against Mr. Weah had been transferred to the Douglas County State Court. Ã¢â‚¬Å“He is not in our jail anymore,Ã¢â‚¬Â a representative at the court told FrontPageAfrica.  The official declined to state how long Mr. Weah spent in the county jail but only added that the matter was forwarded to the county court for trial.

Jannissa Miller, a Clerk at the county court when contacted Wednesday, confirmed WeahÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s case number and added that Mr. Weah is due to appear in court next year. Asked for specifics, Miller said: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Right now it is listed for January but that could change depending on lawyers or the judge.Ã¢â‚¬Â

FrontPageAfrica was not able to confirm how long Mr. Weah spent in the county jail and when he was bailed out or who bailed him out of jail. But legal experts say, penalties for Driving on a Suspended License ranges from jail time to fines.

author: E Bill Tubman

report: People need to remember that Liberia is a fledgling democracy.  Shutting down radio stations may not be the politically correct thing to do, HOWEVER, in this United States, no one and I mean NO ONE can threaten the President without repercussion.  Liberia cannot afford to go back to the days of lawlessness.  It is imperative that this beautiful country remain war free!  When I saw what happened at the CDC HQ I was saddened by the death of innoncent lives, but what angered me was the fact that these people who claim to love Liberia could allow these young children, who idolize Weah, to be used as pawns.  Let us remember our youth and how impressionable we were.  These children need to be groomed and molded into productive citizens, and not become hooligans throwing rocks.  This solves nothing.  Channel that energy, for the good of mankind.  Today may not be your day, but that should not stop you working towards tomorrow and a better Liberia.  Hone those powerful voices into something worth while that will bring pride and honor not death and destruction.  May the souls of those lost in Liberia be forever remembered and may we never return to those days.

report:
SOMEBODY SHOULD HAVE AVOIDED SOMETHING

I regret the lost of lives during the protest/demonstration/peaceful match or maybe peaceful demonstration. I equally sympathize with Mr. George Kailando for the looting of his properties. I sympathize with those peaceful non CDCians and non military persons who vehicles and other properties were destroyed. I say sorry to those peaceful citizens whose movements were restricted by road blocks placed by " peaceful demonstrators"  infront of the CDC headquater. why are people only talking about the boy who lost his live and thinking that the looting of Mr. kailondo;s property was right? Why are we not talking about those who were denied passage infront of the CDC headquater because of the road blocks? Why are we blinding our minds to the plight of those whose vehicles were damage and not by security people. Let me let you know that people were victimized, many people were victimized. While it is true that the death of the CDCian is of great concern, I'm  equally concern with other victms who suffered because some people were exercising some " right to assemble". While it is true that a part of the constitution gives right to peaceful assembly, the constitution also ask that you get permit from the government. While many may think that CDC's action was not a campaign, let us not forget that CDC is a political party and not a church group and these are political times. Getting in the street in the name of peaceful assembly to express anything relative to the election in Liberia was a form of campaign and the laws were clear that campaign was closed. Leaving all those days of campaign and selecting the day you were not to get to the street, was provocative and it was pushing somebody to the wall. fellow Liberia, let us say no to violence and stop doing things that will create the worst case scenario ( DEATH ) just because we want to have reason for saying that somebody is a bad person. a bad person is not a reall bad person when he is pushed to the wall and doing bad becomes a remedy. Blame yourself cuz you forced him to do so. AGAIN, SORRY TO ALL VICTIMS OF THE MONDAY INCIDENCE IN MONROVIA.

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report: Our work speaks. I am in no mood to justify to just every party supporter or loyalists. I think we are gradually degenerating to a society that does not respect contrary opinions. Once the opinion favors UP, I have been lifted in the air like a hollywood celebrity by those sympathetic to UP and obviously berated by those from the CDC. And the reverse is true. We will do our jobs. We have provided in my opinion the most balanced and accurate coverage of events but every single party supporter wants a specific prescription of objectivity and fairness at their standards. Every single party person is skeptical once someone releases a critical opinion. I beg to differ.
author: Lawrence Randall

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report:
Weah Arrested; Trial Set for January

Three weeks ago, FrontPageAfrica received some information that Mr. George Weah, Vice Standard Bearer of the Congress for Democratic Change was arrested in May this year in the U.S. state of Georgia suburban area, Douglas County, and charged with driving while license suspended or revoked(Miscl) and failure to stop at a stop sign.

Weah was booked and an informer provided FrontPageAfrica with the arrest Mug Shot detailing Mr. WeahÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s inmate number as A69806; Race Black, Sex Male, Age of booking at 44, address 1313 NW 139 Terrace Pembrrook Pine, Fl. 33028. The arrest date is listed as 05/09/2011 at 1:47am.

The county SheriffÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s office informed FrontPageAfrica when contacted recently that the case against Mr. Weah had been transferred to the Douglas County State Court. Ã¢â‚¬Å“He is not in our jail anymore,Ã¢â‚¬Â a representative at the court told FrontPageAfrica.  The official declined to state how long Mr. Weah spent in the county jail but only added that the matter was forwarded to the county court for trial.

Jannissa Miller, a Clerk at the county court when contacted Wednesday, confirmed WeahÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s case number and added that Mr. Weah is due to appear in court next year. Asked for specifics, Miller said: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Right now it is listed for January but that could change depending on lawyers or the judge.Ã¢â‚¬Â

FrontPageAfrica was not able to confirm how long Mr. Weah spent in the county jail and when he was bailed out or who bailed him out of jail. But legal experts say, penalties for Driving on a Suspended License ranges from jail time to fines.

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report: Stephen, it is my second time mentioning this. I have over and again, that stations airing inflammatory rhetorics in no help to foster the peace. Kings FM especially have had serious issues with us and even now. The point is, when you reach that tipping point as a government whether to close or not to close, you must consider a lot of things including parity of punishment. As you do not want skpetics to question the intent of your action, you must be pretty sure that it meets tha balance test. That said, as moderate as Power FM, it was closed, so the question rings, what about Truth. SO, it I was in that position, and I must keep the peace, I will ensure the toxic entities are dealt with consistent with law and without exception. But, we can not afford to use illegal means to satisfy legal ends. In the current situation, the government went into over drive.

report:
Liberia Snooped Run-off, Dismal Turnout Nationwide


Monrovia- Liberia turnout in dismal numbers in the much anticipated and controversial presidential run-off election yesterday one day after a bloody clash of state police and partisans of the opposition, now come to be referred to as Ã¢â‚¬Å“Bloody MondayÃ¢â‚¬Â, at the headquarters of the opposition Congress for Democratic Change where state police cracked down on partisans and shot live bullets at the gathering killing seven partisans in counting and injuring several others.

Some polls around the country have to close as early as 12:00 mid-day because there no voters were at the polls, for other polling centers, dozens of voters were seen line in cues to cast their ballots. Several poll workers were seen sleeping because no voters were at the precincts as one poll worker said, Ã¢â‚¬Å“With no voters here and job to do, we eventually get boringÃ¢â‚¬Â.


Full Story: http://thenewdispensation.wordpress.com

report: Is this blind loyalty or love at all cost on the part of some Liberia ? If it was wrong in Samuel Doe's time, Taylor's time, it is surely wrong now inEllenJohnsonSirleaf's. So you think these youths of Liberia (mythys) were killed because they were folled byWinstonTubman and Weah ? How were they fooled, just thinking aloud ? Through a free peaceful assembly ? What are the rules of engaement ? Lets play the devil's advocate and agreed the assembly was wrong; was it right to gun down people, citizens of Liberia because they dared to assembled peacefully ? So death is the sentence now in Liberia when people defied government in a public demostration ? How can any body even attempt to justify this ? is this how we now defend the public peace ? Were these not the same crimes we all fought against yesterday ? The leaders in Liberia today fermented war yesterday in which hundreds of thousands died to address issues they felt strongly against, issues completely the same as is unfolding today, the murdering of the innocents in our country, and people want to justify this ? How do you called what happened on monday, how would you describe it ? What again are the rules of engagement in instances like we witnessed in Liberia on monday ? I am no security personnel, but I know from my studies that you dont use live aminnition at a demostration of unarmed people, even if these people are throwing stones, which in this case did not happen prior to the shootings. Tear gas, is the first response; wipps, water canons' sprayings, to the extreme, the use of rubber bullets; but shots fired, deadly force ? resulting in the death of many, especially Liberia youths ? Well, what path is Liberia treading, a path of peace ? Do you think it is possible in this day and age to subdue people, suppress their thought process through these kinds of murders ? Dont even talk about reconciliation; How can we fix this ? This is a very very grave situation, this is not ordinary platform talk, people died and people are dying as we speak from bullet wounds fired by the Liberia National Police. Say what you may, but this will not lead us to peace anytime soon; besides who ordered these shootings, the discharged of live weapons, ammunitions ? It had to come from the top; and ofcourse there are and will be repercussions. There must be an independent Investigation launched by the United Nations, Amnesty International and other well meaning credible  international groups to ascertain exactly what happened on monday, who instigated what, the rule of law attending, the rules of engagement; who did what, who ordered the killings; so that Liberia can make amends and move forward. We all yearn for peace, but lets be honest, can there ever be peace, real lasting, genuine peace in the absense of justice ? Real lasting peace when other peoples lve ones are murdered in cold blood, what is their crime, just for assembling peacefully to stage a demostration ? HELLO !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! WE WILL SEE !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! MY GOD SAVE OUR CHILDREN AND LOVE ONES.

In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)
