report: Liberia will never become a one party state, just remove that from your thought processes. Everybody in Liberia cannot ever belong to one party; if that happens we will not be talking democracy my people. Democracy means variety, plurality, it certainly does not mean enmity. As it is now in Liberia, once you are not a Unity Party supporter or sympathiser you an enemy of the state, no good, no brains. This will not and cannot continue. I am not a Unity Party partisan, I am a Cdcian, if that makes me an enemy of the state so be it. But Have I broken any law or laws of the republic, why are people looking at me as an enemy of the state ? Being a member of the Congress for Democratic Change means I am not a good law abiding citizen, does it mean I am not voting wisely, does being a member of the Congress for Democratic Change means I am not thinking wisely, or that I am not equally as other Liberia concern about the future of my children and that of my community, and/or my country ? Are you serious when you say once i preferred the CDC, means i am not voting wisely ? These are the foolishness that comes from the mouths of myopic Liberia with the audacity to think that if you are CDC, then you must be a trouble maker; can you imagine this venom ? Well, I am sorry folks if this is your brand of democracy, I would not have any part of it. Now, when WinstonTubman said during the campaign that his government would not prioritize press freedom, everybody bashed him; eventhough he said he was taken out of context, he was still bashed massively by Liberia of all pursuasions. Today, three pradio and telivision facilities were shut down in Liberia under the cover of darkness at about half past 11pm by armed police of the government of Liberia for "hate  speech" according to government sources. Hypocritical, I would say; Hypocritical, yes. How can you shut down radio facilities because in your mind they have alternative views for those of those totting exclusively your line. A week ago a print meduim published a story naming with attending pictures credible Liberia deemed as enemies of peace in Liberia, trouble makers; endangering the lives of these Liberia as a result; this magazine was never closed by government; Truth FM Radio, another meduim of hate speech totting government line 100% is still on the air blabbing hate language and false information, they nevertheless remains on the airwaves of Liberia. How selective can you be, government, in applying justice ? The rule of law cannot be applied selectively, justice is suppose to be blind, thats the true intend and spirit of the law, the courts, etc. Now, in Liberia there is a travesty going on and peaple are attempting to justify this only because they have a piece of job to protect ? Liberia is bigger than all of us if it was wrong yesterday, what makes it right today ? Can peace ever be attain anywhere without some semblance of justice ? Liberia is once again sliding on a slippery slope; all because those who lead want to show that they are iron this, and iron that; well, listen, the time for iron anything is in the past; the application of the law is an across the board situation, it can never be selective; you do it like that you will be found wanting, and mark my word, YOU WILL BE FOUND WANTING; THE DAY OF RECONNING IS UPON US SHORTLY.

Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

A family member and a friend were hurt during the riot (before the incidence between the LNP, UNMIL and the rioters) but they havenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t gone on radio stations to say anything. report:
I do not know the point of contention here. I am gathering that hate speeches in the electoral process is something we should not tolerate because it has the potential to induce violence. If we agree on this point then it is improper to close one station that preaches hate messages and leave another open to continue with hate messages. That said, we should hail the government for closing the three stations initially and press forward for the closure of the remaining stations preaching hate messages. But it would be a weak argument to state that because the others are not closed, so the government should allow all to preach the hate messages. This is unacceptable. Remember it is the gvernment that has to make the closure decisions and not the LP, CDC or any individual. Just as if the CDC was the ruling party, it would be the one clothed with the authority to do same. One hard fact which many people find difficult to hold is when a government is in power,
 all of its decisions will not be liked by everyone. Toga worked for one of the most brutal regimes in Liberia's history and they did what they could from their vintage point. If you ask him now, he will justify every action of the government including the stealing of public funds which he used to build himself a mansion in no time. No one wants to chose a party for you. You have your right as a being to even pursue stupidity if you wish to. But, you have limitations so that you do not infringe on the rights of others. If you are a part of a party that publicly disrespects the government, of course people also have the right to tell you that you are not thinking wisely. Just as you have the right to pursue stupidity, people have the right to tell you that you are pursuing stupidity and you need to change the course of action. It is your right again to say yes or stay put. But clearly, it is now establish locally and internationally that the actions of
 the CDC in these elections have been just unacceptable. Your action to undermine the democratic gains at this time is unfortunate. I am one person with the opinion that despite the leadership chllenges faced by the CDC, they still have the potential to produce leaders in the future, eventhough it may be to my dislike but will have to accept to respect the democratic will of the people. CDC has one nemesis and that has been PresidentEllenJohnsonSirleaf. If PresidentEllenJohnsonSirleaf had stuck to her one term promise, perhaps CDC could be producing the next government. But your actions that have led to the destruction of lives and properties now speak volumes about the inability of the CDC to govern a civilize state.WinstonTubman is not the man and you all know it. You have blown those potentials in the breeze only because guys like you are desperate for power to once again loot the coffers of the nation. However, in Liberia, anything is possible. Refrain from your violent
 approaches and continue to respect law and order until you are elected.
author: Alvin Johnson

report:
Hey Everyone! I wanted to thank you all for using this forum as a platform to communicate your thoughts, challenge each other and even the status quo. As this election season has ended, I have decided to shut down the forum at the end of this month (November 30th).

I know there are groups like http://www.facebook.com/groups/discussingliberia/ (for general Liberia news and politics), http://www.facebook.com/groups/electionsmediamonitoring/ (for Liberia elections), http://www.facebook.com/groups/120274546039/ (youth empowerment and unity discussions), and http://www.facebook.com/groups/Liberiaprofessionalnetwork/ (ONLY for business discussions and professional networking).

Again, it has been a wonderful experience and thanks to all of you for engaging. Even in our disagreement, I hope and pray we always think about Liberia first and put our differences, political parties, views and everything else second.

Thanks,

Taa

report:
Front Page Africa online news: :The Press Union of Liberia has questioned the GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s honesty  about controlling Ã¢â‚¬Ëœhate messageÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ as justification for the overnight  seizure of three media entities in Monrovia and urges the government to  stop its intimidation against the media.
The PUL says the Monday night police action and seizure of the three  media institutions is simply an attempt to silent dissent and force the  media into submission, describing the court order as a cover up.PUL  says while it acknowledges the authority of the court, it warned that  the court and police actions should not go side-by-side and therefore  urges the court to dismiss the unwarranted petition.The PUL  finds it hard to accept that the court would surrender its authority to  the police to invade the premises of the stations and dispossess the  owners of their properties.Notwithstanding the police action,  the Union says it will ensure the appearance of the three institutions  in court on Thursday and calls on all journalists to assemble at the  Court to show solidarity.The Criminal Court Ã¢â‚¬ËœAÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ on Monday night  cited the managements of Sarafina Communications, Royal Communications  and the Infinity Corporation for a conference on November 10 relative to  a petition filed by the Ministries of Justice and Information alleging  Ã¢â‚¬Å“hate message.Ã¢â‚¬ÂMeanwhile the Union has renewed calls for  Liberia journalists to play a stabilizing role especially in the face  of MondayÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s standoff between CDC supporters and the police in Monrovia,  describing the fracas as unfortunate.The Union says the  elections are by now over and journalists need to exercise the highest  degree of social responsibility in handling the aftermath of the  election to avoid any post elections violence.PUL says MondayÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s  incident represents the singular most explosive disruption in the  elections that could degenerate further unless journalists rejected  partisan reporting that would fuel passion.The Union also calls  on Ambassadors WinstonTubman and George Weah to abandon any further  protest action for the sake of the security of their supporters and the  rest of the population.PUL at the same time calls on state  security not to get unnecessarily drawn into the inflammatory comments  coming from politicians to endanger the already fragile peace."

report: Global News Network Liberia: "The opposition Liberty Party (LP) this  week issued added its voice on several issues as its relate to the  growth and development of the Liberia nation, including the recent  closure of three media institutions by the Liberia Government.    Fellow Liberia and Foreign Friends:The Liberty Party  strongly condemns the violence of November 7, 2011 and calls on all,  particularly the national security forces, to exercise restraint and  self-control to ensure that our nation does not return to the days of  fear and instability. We call on the National Legislature to appoint an  independent counsel or committee to probe the violence without delay and  to take the appropriate action to ensure our Nation does not continue  on this path.We regret the loss of lives and destruction of  properties, and extend our prayers and sympathies to all the victims and  their families. of the unfortunate event. We believe such violence  deprives our people of the kind of national conversation that is needed  to further an atmosphere of democracy.The Liberty Party believes  that our NationÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s past of civil conflicts which left many of our fellow  Liberia dead, handicapped, exiled or displaced, is one we cannot  afford to return to. For the sake of our people who are still trying to  mend their lives and are making every effort to nurture our fragile  Ã¢â‚¬Å“DemocracyÃ¢â‚¬Â, the Liberty Party calls on all Liberia not to permit  political differences to supersede our national interest and take us  back to the dark days of our NationÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s history. The government has an especially important responsibility to ensure that the activities of state security remain within the law." Signed,James M.V. YougieDeputy National Secretary General for OperationsLiberty PartySTATEMENT ON THE CLOSURE OF CERTAIN MEDIA INSTITUTIONSLiberty  Party is disturbed by reports that government security forces,  purportedly acting under color of law, has enforced the closure of three  licensed radio stations in Monrovia. We are especially concerned that  such action, coming, as it did, immediately following the reporting by  the media institutions of the violence that led to the death of our  fellow Liberia and the destruction of properties, has the appearance  of an attempt by the Government to muzzle free press. The fact that the  Liberia people were deprived of reporting of election activities on  November 8, 2011, by all media institutions is also sad.We are,  therefore, calling for the immediate reopening of those stations! The  right to freedom of speech and of the press, thought and conscience  without interference of the State is jealously guarded by Article 15 of  the Constitution of our Republic and must be a bedrock tenet of our  fledgling democratic dispensation.The events leading up to the  run-off elections notwithstanding, we must caution the Government that  only a declaration of a State of Emergency can operate to deprive people  of their fundamental rights. In the absence of such declaration, no  legal writ should lie to cause the closure of media institutions and  interfere with that fundamental right of speech, without due process of  law. If individuals take to the public airwaves and engage in hate  speech then they must be held individually responsible. Closing down an  entire station is not the type of individual responsibility envisioned  under our constitution.Liberty Party is fully aware of the  Government's compelling interest in ensuring the security, welfare and  well being of its citizens and all those within our borders. But the  Government must always be cognizant of the constitutional and  fundamental rights of its citizens. The need to act with  restraint and forbearance during these very difficult and volatile times  cannot be overemphasized. Liberty Party calls upon the Government to  exercise restraint in dealing with difficult issues, which traverse our  constitutional framework. Liberia cannot afford to abandon the  democratic path by shutting down radio stations because we dislike the  speech. Such ugliness should be things of our painful past! We call on  the Government to pull away from the brink of what is certainly a  dangerous precipice. Our fledgling democracy must not play into our  worse fears about each other, but engender a spirit of hope in our  future, ever confident that together we can be a great nation. In  our national interest, we call upon the government of President Ellen  EllenJohnsonSirleaf to reopen the closed stations, without delay.Signed,James M.V. YougieDeputy National Secretary General for OperationsLiberty Party

report: Levi, come on now. You know English is our official language. All our legal and casual correspondence, documents, academics and buisness are conducted using that language. Has anyone asked you lately, "what is your official mother tongue"? Yes, I concur we are africans and we have thousands of dialets, but there has to be a language spoken by you that the majority locally and internationally can understand inorder to converse with you.  For us Liberia, English is that language. What you do in your village is unique to your tribe so, definately, is has to be conducted in the dialet/tongue that is dominantly spoken in that setting. Now, see if that works at school, work and play.  Is it too much to ask that the individual that holds the highest office in the land be able to convey a simple message, regardless of accent, that is understood by anyone who speaks that same language?

report:
My views about a better  and reconciled Liberia after these bitter elections:

I think the first task after these bitter elections is reconciliation! Second: creation of job opportunities for unemployed young and adult Liberia, thirdly; improve on our educational system through a more focus on vocational studies for the vast population that is illiterate, and fourth; continue in the path of infrastructural development, etc. If these are prioritized, tensions will automatically reduce and Liberia will be on the right path of development... I submit brodas and sisters on this network! 

If you have any contribution as to the way-forward, please do for the betterment of our beloved country!

report:
My fellow Liberia, the campaign is over, the elections are over, we have one Nation. Let us put aside our differences and move Liberia forward. The only political party we have now is Liberia. There is no UP, CDC, NUDP, LP, NDC, etc but there is Liberia. We have don't it and shown to the world that we are civilize people. If I may take few lines from our National Anthem

IN JOY AND GLADNESS WITH OUR HEARTS UNITED

IN UNION STRONG SUCCESS IS SURE
WE CANNOT FAIL.

WITH HEARTS AND HANDS OUR COUNTRY'S CAUSE DEFENDING

These are strong words. We must keep them, we must uphold them and we must live by these words. It's about time we say 

UNIFICATION, INTEGRATION, RECONCILIATION WILL BRING US PEACE
LET US UNIT AND CLOSELY STAY TIGHT
ONLY LOVE CAN MAKE THIS DREAM RIGHT
JUST LOVE ME FOR ME AND I LOVE YOU FOR YOU
THEN OUR DREAMS WILL COME THROUGH
GOD BLESS LIBERIA.

I want to say to Emmanuel Woods, Moses Massaquoi, Lewis Smith and all other s who has been on this page with me attacking and castigating one another all because we find ourselves on different sides, Ã¢â‚¬Å“WE ARE ALL LiberiaÃ¢â‚¬Â. Liberia is all we have. We are done with politics. It good we have met on this medium. Let's now embrace one another with love in our hearts, peace in our minds and joy in our soul. One Nation, One People. 

LET US RECONCILE OUR POLITICAL DIFFERENCE. 
GOD BLESS US ALL.

report: Moses Carter I am sure u have not taken time to read my post, and for the record, I am a person of law, the best way to halt a media operation is through the courts, so I think in my judgement, the govt acted under the law. Now lets talk the Peter case, I dont see Peter in this matter, I see the PUL. My post didnt mentioned anything about Peter so u are wrong and own me an apology. Secondly, I listen to Mr, Quaqua on Truth FM and read their PUL Press Release which agrees that indeed there are sufficient grounds to close the media houses but the govet needs to include other entities like Truth FM. Now, my point is, if the PUL agrees that these now closed institutions have aired hate messages and violated ethically what did the PUL do in curtailing these professional violations? Is the PUL saying journalists or media institutions can air any anti peace message or violate ethically and its sau nothing but condemn the govt when the court takes an action? where is the best place to carry a media house, I think the court. Peter problem here is why the court used the police? And this is strange to me, becuz of my journalistic coverage of the court, police officers have always been at the court to effect arrest and other actions, why is Peter surprise by this? Its strange to me.

report: At today's hearing for the Radio and Television Stations that were ordered CLOSED by the government of Liberia for spreading hate messages, the entire courtroom went into an uproar when the Solicitor General of Liberia, Wilkins Wright said that the stations should provide evidence. Well, how it sounds when you are taken to court and asked to provide evidence to indict yourself? The burden of proof lies with the accuser so in this case, the government of Liberia should be the one to provide evidence to the court that the stations were indeed spreading hate messages. However, this is another form of muzzling the press and all well meaning Liberia should know this.

report: Big broda, the issue here is about working together. I think the fact that the Government failed to even communicate to the Union of these ethical problems but instead took the decision of shutting those entities down speaks to the fact that they are only willing to cooperate with the Union in some respects but not in important cases as such that require the intervention of the Union. I have also been of the opinion that Peter as head of the Union has been too lenient on dealing with ethical transgressions during the elections. At the media Executive meeting with political stakeholders, that was a major point that I emphasized to him that the Union is responsible for all the ethical bridges that were unfolding. A case in point was the Sam Deen's publication where he reported on his frontpage captioned: "Fromayan Toilet On Himself". I strongly criticized such publication and told Peter that the Union needed to have punished Sam Deen for such publication. These are the things if were done, would have enhance the reportage of media houses in promoting peace. Anyway, thanks for the interaction!

report: The whole distinction regarding mother tongue and official language is just a way of covering up when people do the wrong thing. We all go to school and only learn English throughout. That is just a lame excuse! If someone fails to pay attention to his school work, that's the person's fault, it has nothing to do with the tongue his mother gave him. report: It is unfortunate that Liberia died as a result of complete foolishness displayed by socalled politicians. There was no need for any demonstration. CDC had announced that they would boycott the elections and everybody knew this. They should have press their case further afterwards and inform the international community that the government lacks credibility. CDC knew they wanted this because the call for demonstartion at that crucial time of the elections was intended to disrupt the process and if CDC was a government they could not allow that. The party had made its positions clear that it will not honor anything from the government. That in itself is chaos by itself. Do you expect CDC demonstrators to remain in the compound if the police told them to do so? They would come out to challenge the police because the party officials had told them not to honor anything coming from the government. Unless people are saying here they should have allow the CDC to block the roads and loot people properties as they started to do already when the triot broke out. The police had to quell the situation. Now the circumstances leading to the death of people is what needs to be explained. This is why the investigation is important. Unconfirmed reports I am getting suggest that there were attempts by some CDCians to disarm an officer. Unless Foeday and others also believe that the officer in question, if this is true, should have alowed himself to be disarmed and butchered by the mob. Again, the investigation would not mean anything to CDC because the party does not respect any position coming from the government. I am saddened that Foeday and others would be advocating for a lawless society. The UP government is on records of being the most tolerant government in Liberia's recent past. People have called and abuse the president on talk shows. The CDC chairman and secretary general have abused the office of the presidency and go sound to sleep as long as those actions did not directly affect the peace and stability of the country. An attempt by demonstrators to unlawfully take matters into their own hands and ignore warnings from the international community that is under obligation to protect protesters like in the case of Libya only meant that the government had to take a stance to halt the lawlessness. It has ledto the death of individuals which is regrettable but the government had to act in swift response.
author: Alvin Johnson

report: A little boy goes to his dad and asks, 'what is politics?' Dad says, well son, let me try to explain it this way: I'm the breadwinner of the family, so let's call me capitalism. Your mom, she's the administrator of the money, so we'll call her the Government. We're here to take care of ur needs, so we'll call you the people. The nanny, we'll consider her the working class. And ur baby brother, we'll call him the future. Now, think about that and see if that makes sense. So the little boy goes off to bed thinking about what dad had said. Later that night, he hears his baby brother crying, so he gets up to check on him. He finds that the has severely soiled his diaper. So the little boy goes to his parents' room and finds his mother sound asleep. Not wanting to wake her, he goes to the nanny's room. Finding the door locked, he peeks in the keyhole and sees his father in bed with the nanny. He gives up and goes back to bed. The next morning, the little boy says to his father, 'Dad, I think I undertand the concept of politics now'. The father says, 'Good son' tell me in ur own words what you think politics is all about'. The little boy replies, 'well, while capitalism is screwing the working class, the Government is sound asleep, the people are being ignored and the future is in deep shit'.
author: Manah K O Sambola

report: Stanley, you  are right the Government would always use the law in enforcing the peace.   Doe used the law to close down Daily Observer, Foot Prints and ELCM Radio.  Taylor used the law to shut down Radio Veritas,  Star Radio and your own News Newspaper. During that time, the ministers of Doe and Taylor hailed them for upholding the law. Today, the same ministers say Doe and Taylor  are tyrants.   I do agree that the media should exercise its social responsibility in exercising its freedom.  Frankly with the exception of UNMIL Radio, most media institutions took sides.   They were divided among opposition and government. So when drastic action is taken against one group, it raises the head of the ugly hydra. I also agree that the PUL should not only discuss the shutting down of the media institutions but also discuss the unnecessary violent protest.  We have done much harm to Liberia. It is time that the media help to heal the wounds.

report: @ Benetta Fofana, get me right my dear. I was only objectively analyzing the issues being raised here about Peter's position on the government draconian action. To restate again, I think it is a shared responsibility between the government of Liberia and the Press Union's leadership. My reason is that little efforts were exerted by the union to curtail ethical transgressions of media houses. If they had taken drastic actions on media houses threading in unethical reporting,  today, we would not have reach this far. I even emphasized this to Peter on last Saturday at the Media Executive Meeting at the Corina Hotel, but  he thought I was joking. I told Peter that politicians will always remain politicians. They deal in rhetorics and  act like they are sincere about issues and collaboration. Including the Ministry of Information, the Government of Liberia is a threading much in rhetorics than sincerity in the way issues are addressed. I believe, if some do not have much to provide the discussion here, its better for them to remain quiet.

report: Bomi County has just completed final tally of the run-off election in Liberia. NEC Bomi Magistrate Washington Farmah minutes ago confirmed the completion of all 128 precincts in the county, noting that results are being posted at the electoral wash dogÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s sub-office inWinstonTubmanburg. He expressed optimism that the county will be featured in this eveningÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s announcement of provisional results at HQ in Monrovia. ECOWAS, Election Coordinating Committee (ECC), Carter Centre, the Liberia Council of Churches (LCC) and the Unity Party (UP) amongst other observers he said persistently monitored the tally. Meanwhile, the NEC Bomi boss has said ballot boxes will remain at the county level for a period of six-months for the sake of future reference just in case the need arises.

report: Isaac, my simple point here is that the regimes used the issue of the law in protecting the public peace. They would always craft writs in carrying out their plans. During DoeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s era, senior journalists were officials (post and telecommunication, information, director general  lbs, ambassador at large) And the TaylorÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s era (minister of information, chief of staff vice presidentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s office,  deputy minister of state).  None of these journalists spoke in the collective interest of journalists.   Journalism like any other profession will have some low days.  I do agree with you that the unprofessional behavior should not go unnoticed. We should unearth them and be magnanimous in accepting corrections in making speedy progress.   But in doing this, our lenses should focus on all sides even if they are favorable or unfavorable to our taste.

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)

report:
Following Liberia's November 8th run-off election, the first round of election results has just been release by Liberia's National Election Commission (NEC), putting incumbent President EllenJohnsonSirleaf ahead with 513,320 votes representing 90.8%, while Opposition Congress for Democratic Change (CDC) thrills with 52,71 votes representing 9.2% of total votes counted thus far. The total votes just released represent 32% of the entire votes expected in shortly.

It was also announced that the opposition CDC  has finally withdrew her case from the NEC and is now taking it to the Supreme Court, where it is expected to be determined in several days time, according to Liberia electoral laws. The electoral body has accordingly made a determination on it already in which it was established that no incident of fraud was observed during the first round of voting in Liberia. Thumbs up to the electoral body for it splendid performance to uphold Liberia's nursing democracy.

Courtesy: AFP

Monrovia-Liberia awaited results of a presidential run-off poll on Wednesday set to hand incumbent EllenJohnsonSirleaf a tough second term after police admitted firing live bullets at opposition protesters.

Police Chief Marc Amblard admitted that live bullets had been fired into a crowd of opposition protesters which turned violent on the eve of the election, saying police had seen no bodies, while the opposition says up to four died.

report:
Liberia MEDIA UNDER SERIOUS ATTACK... GOVERNMENT REFUSED TO PRODUCE EVIDENCE

The Government of Liberia has failed to produce evidence against three media institutions it says were broadcasting inflammatory and hate  messages a day before the run-off elections.

Appearing before the Criminal Court A Thursday, the government represented by Solicitor General Wilkins Wright ordered the court to issue a subpoena requesting the stations to produce evidence against themselves.

THIS IS A REPORT

The criminal court A at the Temple of Justice was a dramatic scene today when the government of Liberia represented by solicitor general Wilkins Wright failed to produce substantive evidence in the case involving the closure of three media institutions by the government.

The court jam-packed with local and international journalists along with legal minds witnessed what should have been a conference between media managers and the government but eventually turned into a hearing where Cllr. Wright and prosecution team raised several motions and injections asking the defendants; Power TV, Kings FM and Love FM to produce evidence.

The Prosecution Cllr. Wright asked the court to issue a writ on the three media institutions to produce evidence; something which legal minds termed as a scare tactics on the part of government to muster the press.

Peter Quiqui in a very disturbed mood questioned the credibility of government.

The Press Union of Liberia President reemphasized that the move by the Unity Party led government is intended to intimidate the media.

Mr. Quiqui termed the government the government decision to shut-down the media institutions as strange and very troubling for Liberia's democracy.

Aaron Kollie, a veteran Liberia Journalist and owner of the Infinity Corporation - Power FM/TV called on the EllenJohnsonSirleaf led government to with immediate effect open the media institutions.

He said the government action is pre-medidated and intended to clam-down on the Press something which it has boost for over the years.

The Criminal Court A has adjourned the case to a later date.

According to 15 section c of the 1986 Liberia Constitution; there shall be no limitation on the public right to be informed about government and its functionaries; but critics are wondering whether this right will be achieved by the Unity Party led government with latest action.
author: Moses Browne

report:
NATIONAL ELECTIONS COMMISSION

National Tally Center Tally Progressive Report
for the Run-off Election of the President and Vice-President

3,859 of 4,457 Polling Places Reported

on 08 November 2011
10 Nov 2011 5:00 p


Presidential Candidate
Vice-Presidential Candidate Political Party Votes %

JOHNSON-SIRLEAF, Ellen
BOAKAI, Joseph Nyema Unity Party (UP) 513,320 90.8%

TUBMAN, WinstonTubmanA.
WEAH, George Manneh Congress for Democratic Change (CDC) 52,071 9.2%

Total Valid Votes
565,391 100.0%

Invalid Votes *
21,673

Total Votes
587,064

* Invalid votes account for 3.7% of total votes.





Cllr. Elizabeth J. Nelson

Acting Chairman, National Elections Commission (NEC)


Ladies and Gentlemen of the Press, My Fellow Liberia

The National Elections Commission wishes to congratulate all registered voters that turned out to vote in the Presidential Run-off Election conducted on November 8, 2011, for their patriotism and good deportment exhibited during the election.

The Commission further wishes to express heartfelt thanks to all field staff including poll workers, many of whom spent sleepless hours in ensuring that the election succeeded.   

Special thanks and appreciation go to the leadership and officers of the joint security forces for helping to provide the enabling environment for the successful conduct of the Presidential Run-off election.

To our international partners, observer groups and the media, we sincerely appreciate your role and involvement throughout the process.

Distinguished ladies and gentlemen of the press, we are pleased to report that the electoral process has been successfully implemented as planned. Polls opened in most places on time and since we had only one ballot paper with two candidates in the race, the counting of votes has been much faster this time. 

PROVISIONAL RESULTS

As reported during our briefing to the press on Tuesday, November 8, 2011, immediately following the close of the polls, the reconciliation, sorting and counting of votes commenced at all polling places across the country. The result of each polling place was placed on the wall for public viewing, in addition to distribution of copies to party agents that were present. The original copy of results from each polling place was placed in a Tamper Evident Envelope and taken to the magisterial tally center for processing.

The tallying of election results commenced across the country early Wednesday morning at all magisterial tally centers in the presence of local and international observer groups, the media, as well as party agents.

I must clarify that because the run-off was one election with only two candidates in the race, the tally process is also proceeding much faster than during the October 11 elections.

I wish to remind the parties that complaints regarding polling/counting or tallying irregularities should be filed with the NEC Magistrate Offices. We further wish to report that to date, the NEC has received no complaints regarding the November 8, 2011 Presidential Run-off Election.

The National Elections Commission will now proceed with the announcement of the first provisional results from the November 8, 2011 Presidential Run-off Election.

report: What is Reconciliation in your mind ? Somebody please define Reconciliation for me. Dont forget the people of Liberia are not enemies and will never be enemies of one another for no reason, yes we will disagree on the path of our country from time to time, but naturally, we remain brothers and sisters. But what brand of reconciliation are you referring to ? The one where state police killed in cold blood innocent, unarmed Liberia whose only crime was  to assembled and raised their objection peacefully ? Oh so now its time to let by gones be bygones, anyso ? Or are we talking the reconciliation where the fourth estate refused to play by the rules, their independent roles, as watch dogs of society; thus assuring an equitable and just society but rather dabble in kato and yellow journalism ? And now this same fourth estate is now doing the bidding (Public relations) for the same govermnment, guilty of killing the innocent ones; now calling for reconciliation, is this the reconciliation you are talking about ? Or reconciliation has all of a sudden now become paramount now that the madamEllenJohnsonSirleaf has won the election by whatever means ? ITS TIME FOR NATION BUILDING NOW, NOT SO ? IS THIS YOUR BRAND OF RECONCILIATION ? What is reconciliation to you ? When one group continues to monopolise state resources at the disadvantaged of the vast majority of the people of Liberia; in your mind will that ever result into reconciliation ? One group presiding over all the resources and not bothering to open the economic net to other capable Liberia, infact leaving all perceived enemies of the the state out; yet you sit there and talk about reconciliation ? Dear what do you understand reconciliation to mean ? You balling from the country's resources whilst aother people continue to wallor in poverty; yet you are calling for a national conference, to talk about what, reconciliation ? A lot of Liberia were killed in cold blood on monday this week by state security personnel, investigations is not ongoing from any credible independent group; no finding/s have been declared, we dont as yet know what the president role was, who ordered the murders of these innocent CDCIANS/Liberia, why live ammunitions were used, all these are questions yet to be unanswered; in the absense of this how can you realistically call for reconciliation ? Reconciation with whom ? they say what goes around comes around; you ever heard of that ? Reconciliation on what basis ? At the bidding of the cold blooded manipulative victor or the maligned victim (the people of Liberia ) ?

report:
Thanks to all Upians who fought this Election battle, we held strong together, we fuss, we were insulted, we insulted too, we give love, we received love, we shared views, we accepted others views, we agree, we disagree, now lets UNITE with our opponents
and include them into our regime with love and respect. At the end of the day we are all still Liberia. Rome wasn't built in one day. Mission is accomplished. Love you all. Now it's time for us to bring back the reason why we are all on Facebook, reconnecting, hustling chamos, looking for man, old schoolmates, old neighborhood friends, finding lost family members and just posting crazy fun to clear the stress this world has to offer, and we give God the praises, and sympathize with the family that lost their love one during this time. Thank you God for us yahhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhh. I Macdonald Muana Goodridge faithfully approve this message. Sign and Notorized in spirit by Her Excellency President of The Republic of Liberia Madam EllenJohnsonSirleaf our NOBLE PEACE AWARD WINNER. God Bless. I Thank You. hmm tha another 6 years ohh, who's next in line Upians? hm

report: Deddeh Howard, you took the observation out my mouth. It's good that you pointed it out, because I would've never said it like the way you did. Just to add on; this is the reason why some Liberia haven't been so successful at public speaking,,, They find it difficult to connect just by the things they say or how they said it. My dad told me a very funny story; he said one Mr. Zarpah Liberty (stand to be corrected on the first name spelling) came to speak to freshman students at LU. Through out his hour long speech, he used so so big big vocab which deprived a lot of students from understanding what he was saying. Yet, according to my dad, some of his peers kept clapping at the use of a big word. After the speech, my dad decided to ask one of the guys who was sitting next to him, who happens to be one of those clapping. He asked,"What was honorable Liberty actually saying, did you understand him?" The guy replied, "I really didn't understand half of what the man said, but the man know book ma man." LOL!!! LMBO!!!! Look, that was the most hilarious thing I ever heard!!! How in the world you don't understand what somebody is saying, yet you clapping at what he's saying? I didn't have the privilege of growing up in Liberia like others, but it seems this is the way they show others how educated they are. Speaking all those big vocabs in the wrong context. Words means a whole lot and I respect that, but there is a place and time to speak like that. The funny part is most of them can't even open their mouths' when they're are around real academics, but they tried to kill us with their so called big big english... I just be reading laughing out loud. Stephen Johnson, do you know who Mr.Zarpah Liberty is? lol

It would be the biggest political mockery of the century if CDC elected lawmakers take their seats amidst the controversy surrounding the October 11 elections which the party claimed was characterized by irregularities. report: My brother, I tried the best that I can to avoid participating in  discussions that is off no substance. Like everyone on this forum, I reserved the rights to comment or not on any post, and I exercised such right on this post. I didn't mentioned your name any where in my previous comments, but you took the time to address me, and I responded accordingly. As the self imposed President of the product of your equation, I would think you would've been able to determined when an accusation is actually being made, but your lack of understanding have lead you the wrong way. Again, if i may ask; why are you the only one so adamate about the simple point being made on this post? To the extend where you went out your way to make mentioned of me? That is enough reason to assume that this post affected you and your usage of words ineffectively. I rested my case because I don't have the time to engage you insubstantially. If you really wish to engage with me, I suggest we discuss something that will be a benefit to Liberia. Like educational reform in Liberia, ways we can get kids who lack the financial means to develop themselves off the streets and in the class rooms, In which capacities can we as citizens help in creating jobs, opening businesses in Liberia etc... I'm more than ready to engage you on these important issues. Not one where we have a sensitive guy making something out of nothing. BTW, FB is not where i use big words to impress my friends, I use them when its necessary. I hope I was clear for your understanding Mr. Varney Clarke. Now, are you ready to discuss those issues I suggested?

report: While Killing is never necessary, you can not ignore  the fact that the police was provoked to retaliate in the way they did.  1.Our Constitution is meant to be the backbone of our society, its meant to represent us as a culture,as a race of people with one common goal. we are suppose to uphold it as part of us. when people start breaking that down , does that not break our culture? why did we have to change the rules for a few. The elections guidelines are deprived form our Constitution we are meant to uphold it. our nation will never grow if we do not start upholding  our own laws and regulations; which is the social contract mandated to keep all men/women free in our country, when we start tearing that social contract down does it not take rights away from the people who decided to follow it.the elections where meant to be held on the day it held because that is what was agreed on.  .If we start breaking the basic foundation of rules and regulations that are put in place to govern us, when will we stopWhen will we start be law abiding. when will we have structure if we don't let our backbones to grow through our constitution. WHEN will it stop, when will we stop letting personal emotions and ego govern us. the right to voter is the voice that every Liberia has. why would you muzzle that right.2. from my understand in Liberia in order to protest you need to register and be recognized( this is also one of our social contract , put in place to keep people safe) this was never met  by the protesters.you as a citizen can do whatever you want in you yard but once you bring it to the public it is the government job to make sure that the public is not in danger, which from my understanding is what the police was doing. this all has to do with following the rules that are put in place to guide us as a nation. if we dont have these rules, than what expresses us as a nation?

report:
LMC/CEMESP Condemn Govt. Systematic Media Clampdown
Monrovia, Liberia
November 9, 2011
The Liberia Media Center and the Center for Media Studies and Peace Building categorically condemn the Liberia Government for the illegal closure of four broadcast entities in Liberia. 
In a petition filed before the judge of Criminal Court A on November 7, 2011, the state sought the permanent cancellation of the broadcast licenses of the four institutions claiming that the respondents illegally used their respective media outlets to broadcast hate messages against the Government and deliberately disseminated misinformation and messages of violence, instigating the people to rise up and take to the streets, amongst others.
In its petition, the State prayed that the court grant a request for temporary closure of the institutions pending a hearing, and subsequent to the hearing, ordered a permanent closure of Power FM and TV Station, Love FM and TV, Kings FM and Clar TV and Shatta FM.
Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)
author: Lawrence Randall

Having reviewed the merits of the petition, LMC and CEMESP unequivocally condemn governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s action to shut down the media outlets as this action clearly infringes on the petitionerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right to due process.
While the LMC and CEMESP frown on the spreading of inflammatory rhetorics on the radio and in the newspaper, we are equally alarmed by the arbitrariness of governmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s actions and the Criminal CourtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s illegal granting of a legally defective petition. In its petition the Government of Liberia failed to state the law that was violated in count three of its petition.
Further, GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition was defective as it failed to disclose a concise Ã¢â‚¬Å“cause of action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  According to Civil Procedure Law Section 16.5Ã¢â‚¬Â-each petition shall comply with the rules of a complaint in an action.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This means there must clearly be a stated action, in which this petition failed to provide. GovernmentÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s petition which reads: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Petition for the closure of communications entitiesÃ¢â‚¬Â, sought a remedy, but did not state a cognizable cause of action.  
Especially disturbing was the fact that the petition for injunction and a temporary restraining order, usually reserved for civil suits, was filed in the criminal court.  Essentially it means that the court did not and does not have jurisdiction over the subject matter. According to the Liberia Law Revised, Volume 40, in the case of Lamin v. Save the Children fund, the Supreme Court stated that Ã¢â‚¬Å“circuit courts are statutory courts which derive their being and scope of powers from the statues creating them and cannot exercise jurisdiction beyond what is conferred by statute (Lamin et al Save The Children Fund UK, 1996).  The fact that the petition circumvents that fact makes it null and void from its very existence.  

Furthermore, assuming that criminal charges have been levied against the respondents, there has been no writ of summons or arrest issued against them. This writ of summons would have effectively brought the respondents or defendants under the courtÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s jurisdiction (Honor. Alexander Zoe v. George Tulay, 1997).   Failure to do so, regardless if the criminal court was the proper jurisdiction, is a blatant error.
The Government also failed to mention the exact penal code the respondents violated.  Once again the fact that such words like petitioner and respondents were used clearly demonstrate that this was a civil matter and the court in this instance lacks jurisdiction over this matter. 
 Liberia Code of Laws Revised, Criminal Procedure Section 14.4 clearly states that Ã¢â‚¬Å“The written complaint shall specify the nature of the offense charged and shall contain a concise statement of the acts of the defendant alleged to constitute such offense, and of the time and place of the commission of the offense, and of the time and place of commission of the offense and of the person, if any, against whom, and the thing, if any, in respect to which, the offense was committed.Ã¢â‚¬Â  This procedure was not followed.
The fact that the petition was filed in the wrong court (criminal instead of civil) which lacked jurisdiction, coupled with serious defects such as lack of stated action, the fact that no charge or complaint was filed, and no rule of law or penal code cited, renders the whole petition defective and void ab initio.  The judgeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s granting of the temporary restraining order that temporarily closed these media outlets has no basis in law and thus should be immediately rescinded.  
Finally, LMC and CEMESP believe the Liberia Government acted to close the four broadcast entities in a drastic attempt to suppress speech, muzzle the press, violate fundamental freedom and crush dissent.  The action should be immediately rescinded and the Liberia Government should issue a public apology for this gross violation of fundamental rights.

Signed:_________________________________
 Lawrence Randall
 Executive Director, Liberia Media Center (LMC)

Signed:___________________________________________________
 Malcolm Joseph 
 Executive Director, Center for Media Studies and Peace Building (CEMESP)
